Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 b5 7. Bb3 d6 {[%csl Rb3,Ge5][%cal Gd7d6,Gd6e5,Rc6a5,
Ra5b3]} 8. a3 (8. a4 b4 9. a5 {[%csl Ga5,Ra6,Rb4][%cal Ga8b8,Gb8b5,Gb5a5]})
8... O-O 9. Nc3 Na5 {[%csl Ga5][%cal Gc6a5]} 10. Ba2 Be6 11. b4 (11. Bxe6 fxe6
{[%cal Gd8e8,Ge8g6,Gf6h5,Gh5f4,Gf8f1]}) 11... Bxa2 12. Rxa2 Nc6 13. Bg5 Nd7 {
[%csl Re7,Rg5][%cal Re7g5,Rg5e7]} ({The two GMs already discussed this opening
before. In Leon Aronian chose instead:} 13... Qd7 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Nd5 Bd8 16.
a4 Ne7 17. Ne3 Rb8 18. axb5 axb5 19. c3 Qe6 20. Qb1 d5 {and held the game to a
draw later, Anand,V (2785)-Aronian,L (2804) Bilbao 2014}) 14. Bd2 {[%csl Gd2]}
Nf6 {[#]} 15. Nd5 $146 ({The predecessor was:} 15. Re1 Qd7 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17.
exd5 Na7 18. a4 c6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc6d5]} 19. axb5 axb5 20. Qa1 cxd5 21. Be3
d4 22. Nxd4 exd4 23. Bxd4 Bf6 24. Bxf6 gxf6 25. Qxf6 Rfe8 26. Qg5+ Kf8 27. Qh6+
Kg8 28. Qg5+ Kf8 29. Qh6+ Kg8 30. Qg5+ {1/2-1/2 (30) Naiditsch,A (2721)
-Wojtaszek,R (2727) Douglas 2018}) 15... Nxd5 16. exd5 Nb8 17. c4 Nd7 18. Qb3
f5 19. Rc2 Bf6 20. Be3 {[%csl Ge5,Rf2,Gf5,Rg2,Gg7,Rh2,Gh7] In a Najdorf-type
of position Black has the kingside majority and his attack is running smoothly
there.} g5 {[%csl Rc5,Rc7,Rd6,Ge5,Gf5,Gg5][%cal Gg5g4,Gf5f4,Rc4c5] "I thought
allowing this is really dangerous" (Aronian)} 21. h3 h5 22. cxb5 ({The
Armenian GM believed White should have tried to stop his attack with} 22. h4 $5
gxh4 23. Rfc1 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gg8h8,Gd8e7,Ge7g7,Gf8g8,Gg8g1] and he might
well be right.}) 22... g4 23. hxg4 hxg4 24. Nh2 axb5 25. Rfc1 Bg5 26. Rxc7 ({
Black expected} 26. d4 exd4 27. Bxg5 Qxg5 28. Rxc7 Ne5 {[%csl Ge5,Rg1,Rh2]
[%cal Gd4d3,Ge5c4,Gf5f4,Gg4g3] when thanks to the huge knight he is much
better.}) 26... g3 27. Nf1 ({Tactics does not solve White problems as after} 
27. Rxd7 Qxd7 28. Bxg5 gxh2+ 29. Kh1 f4 {[%csl Rg5] the white bishop is also
trapped.}) ({If} 27. Nf3 gxf2+ 28. Kxf2 Bxe3+ 29. Kxe3 {The white king is
getting dragged out. Aronian planned the simple:} Nf6 {with many threats.} ({
But even better would be:} 29... e4 $1 30. dxe4 fxe4 {Now if White is brave
enough and gets the pawn:} 31. Kxe4 {He would easily get mated:} ({Aronian was
afraid of} 31. Qc2 {but there is the simple} Rxa3+ {[%csl Re3][%cal Ra3e3]})
31... Qf6 32. Rxd7 Rfe8+ 33. Kd3 Qg6+ 34. Kd2 ({Or} 34. Kd4 Re4+ 35. Kd3 Rxb4+)
34... Qxg2+ 35. Kc3 Rac8+ 36. Kd4 Qf2+ 37. Kd3 Qe3# {[%csl Rd3]})) 27... gxf2+
28. Kxf2 Bxe3+ 29. Nxe3 Qh4+ {[%csl Rf2] Once again the white king got
extricated from the good defensive position. The end is near.} 30. Ke2 f4 31.
Nd1 f3+ {A bit rushy and based on miscalculation.} (31... Nf6 {[%csl Gf6] was
not bad at all.}) ({The easiest win was to improve the queen first:} 31... Qg4+
32. Ke1 Qg3+ 33. Ke2 (33. Kd2 Qxg2+ 34. Kc3) {Then tear apart the white
king's position-} 33... f3+) 32. gxf3 Rxf3 {The point, which is the actual
mistake.} ({It was not too late to insert a check} 32... Qh2+ 33. Nf2 {Then
take:} Rxf3 $1 {With the seconds ticking away Aronian was afraid of:} 34. Rc8+
{But he could have won with} Rf8) 33. Rc8+ ({Anand could have just taken it.
After:} 33. Kxf3 Rf8+ 34. Ke2 Qh2+ 35. Ke1 Qg2 36. Rc8 $1 {Comes in time and
defends the king. Then} Qf1+ 37. Kd2 Qg2+ {would be perpetual.}) 33... Rf8 34.
Rxa8 Qh2+ $1 {There is no second chance for the former world champion. The
in-between check does not allow any coordination.} ({Although} 34... Rxa8 35.
Nf2 Qh5+ {would be big advantage for Black too.}) 35. Ke1 Rxa8 36. Rc2 Qg3+ 37.
Rf2 ({The last chance was:} 37. Kf1 Rf8+ 38. Rf2 Nf6 39. Qc2 {although it is
hard to believe that all the black pieces will not find a way through the
white king.}) 37... Nf6 38. Kf1 Ng4 0-1

