Nxe3 Ne6 11. O-O-O c5 12. g3 Nd4 13. Nxd4 cxd4 14. Ng2 Be6 15. Kb1 Qe7 16. f4
O-O-O 17. Nh4 g6 18. Nf3 Rd6 19. fxe5 fxe5 20. Nxe5 Bxa2+ 21. Kxa2 Qxe5 {
Anand,V (2757)-So,W (2760) Bucharest 2019}) 7. O-O Bd6 8. d4 Nd7 9. dxe5 Nxe5
10. Nxe5 Bxe5 11. f4 Bd4+ 12. Kh1 f5 13. Qh5+ g6 14. Qe2 O-O 15. Nf3 Bf6 16. e5
{[%csl Ge5,Gf4] With more or fewer pieces on the board, but the Berlin pawn
structure arose again. White has a defended passer on the kingside and Black
can hardly make anything out of his queenside pawns in a possible endgame.} Be7
17. Rd1 Qe8 18. Nd4 Qf7 19. Nxe6 Qxe6 20. Be3 {[#]} Rad8 $146 {Technically
speaking, a novelty.} ({Which does not change the general picture already seen
in the predecessor:} 20... Rfd8 21. c4 a6 22. b3 Kf7 23. a4 Ke8 24. h3 Rxd1+
25. Rxd1 Rd8 26. Rxd8+ Bxd8 27. Bc5 Kf7 28. Qd2 Bh4 29. Kh2 h5 {Caruana,F 
(2787)-Grischuk, A (2750) London 2015}) 21. c4 a6 22. b3 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5][%cal
Gb3c4,Gc4d5] Anand is depriving his opponent of any active possibilities along
the d-file. With the d5 square covered So cannot double effectively his rooks
and massive exchanges are about to happen along the d-file.} Kf7 23. h3 h5 24.
Bf2 Rxd1+ 25. Rxd1 Rd8 26. Rxd8 Bxd8 27. Qe1 {[%csl Rd8,Re1,Re6,Rf2][%cal
Gh1h2,Gh2g3,Gg3h4,Gh4g5] Everything goes according to the plan. If White
manages to get rid of all the remaining pieces he will win. Another plan is to
try and penetrate with the queen into the enemy camp. So has to be careful.}
Qe7 {A slight inaccuracy. So did not want to allow the bishop sortie on h4.} ({
He did not have to fear it though in the line:} 27... Qd7 28. Bh4 Be7 $1 ({
But not:} 28... Bxh4 29. Qxh4 {[%cal Rh4g5,Rg5h6] Which only helps White
infiltrate with his queen, as the second player needs to avoid the pawn
endgame as the plague:} Qe7 $2 30. Qxe7+ Kxe7 31. Kh2 h4 32. g3 {[%cal Gh2g3,
Gg3h4,Gh4g5] and White wins.})) 28. Kh2 Ke6 29. Qd2 {Black's pieces look
awkward. So tries to co-ordinate them.} Qd7 {And blunders.} (29... Qf8 $1 {
was a must with the idea to meet the active:} 30. Qa5 {with the
not-less-active:} Qh6 {[%csl Rf4,Rh2][%cal Rh6f4]}) 30. Qb4 $1 {A double
attack which nets a pawn.} Kf7 ({As otherwise Black may lose more than one
footsoldier in the line:} 30... b6 31. Qf8 Qe7 32. Qg8+) 31. Qxb7 Qd2 {The
only chance is in the activity.} 32. e6+ $1 {A nice shot by Anand.} ({The
immediate:} 32. Bg1 $5 Qxf4+ 33. Kh1 {would have been good for White as well.})
({But not:} 32. Bg3 $2 h4) 32... Kg7 {Now it seems as the American GM will be
able to create a perpetual check.} ({White's task is easier after:} 32... Kxe6
33. Qxc6+ Kf7 34. Qc5 Qxf4+ 35. Bg3) 33. Bg1 $1 {Nope, Anand is immediately
spotting the best continuation.} Qxf4+ 34. Kh1 Qd6 35. Qxa6 Qxe6 36. Qa7 g5 {
One last try to open the white king and deliver perpetual.} 37. a4 g4 38. Qe3
$1 {White is aware and leaves his opponent no chances at all.} ({After
something natural like:} 38. a5 $2 gxh3 39. gxh3 Qe4+ 40. Kh2 Qf4+ {Black is
safe.} ({And he can even think for more in the line:} 40... Bf6 41. Qxc7+ Kh6))
38... Qc8 (38... Qxe3 39. Bxe3 {is hopeless for Black.}) 39. Qe8 gxh3 40. Bd4+
{It is White's turn to attack.} Kh6 41. Bf6 {The simplest.} ({There was also a
forcing mate with:} 41. Qh8+ Kg5 42. Qg7+ Kf4 43. Qe5+ Kg4 (43... Kg5 44. Qg3+
Kh6 45. Qg7#) 44. gxh3+ Kxh3 45. Qe2 $1) 41... hxg2+ 42. Kxg2 f4 {One last
perpetual option maybe?} 43. Qg8 {Nope again.} Qd7 44. Qg5+ {Winning by force
as demonstrated by the former world champion:} Kh7 45. Qxh5+ Kg8 46. Qh8+ Kf7
47. Qg7+ Ke6 48. Qxd7+ Kxd7 49. Bxd8 Kxd8 50. Kf3 1-0

