Rea1 {The simple tripling of the major pieces is a deadly threat for Black.
Therefore, he needs to step on the mined square with his bishop:} Bb6 {And it
seems as it will work as the second white rook on a1 is now en prise in case of
the capture on b6.} ({The in-between capture:} 20... exd4 {Was a try as well,
when after:} 21. cxd4 Bb6 22. Rxa8 Rxa8 23. Rxa8+ Qxa8 24. e5 ({However, in
this case, White can use another strong idea:} 24. d5 $1 Bxe3 25. dxe6 Bb6 26.
exf7+ Kxf7 27. Nf5 {with a clear edge for the first player.}) 24... dxe5 25. dxe5
Bxe3 26. exf6 Qa1+ 27. Nf1 Bf4 {Black should be able to survive.}) 21. Rxa8
Rxa8 22. Rxa8+ Qxa8 23. dxe5 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Re5f6] So wins a pawn and in the
process destroys the opponent's castling. The win is within his reach.} Qa1+ ({
Or:} 23... Bxe3 24. exf6 Bg5 25. fxg7 Qa1+ 26. Bf1 Bf6 27. Nd4 {with a huge
advantage for White.}) 24. Bf1 Bxe3 25. exf6 Bb6 ({Perhaps Black should have
switched to the line from above:} 25... Bg5 26. fxg7 Bf6 27. Nd4 {as the
dark-squared bishop is at least protecting the king in this line.}) 26. fxg7
Ne5 27. Qd2 {Going for the king at once.} ({Here too, the centralization:} 27.
Nd4 $1 Bxd4 28. cxd4 Qxd4 29. Nh5 Qc5 30. Qd1 {would have led to a win for
White. Next, he will prepare the advance of the f-pawn and slowly squeeze his
opponent.}) 27... Nxf3+ 28. gxf3 Kxg7 29. Kg2 $1 {An important move in So's
plan. White is unpinning his bishop and it will be a key piece in the attack.}
b4 $1 {The last chance! A second pawn is sacrificed but the queen gains access
to the kingside. Carlsen clearly understands that without some help from the
pieces he will be mated.} ({For instance:} 29... Qa7 30. Nh5+ Kh7 ({Or:} 30...
Kg6 31. f4 Kxh5 32. f5 {and the lonely king cannot survive.}) 31. Bd3 {with
the unstoppable e4-e5+ and mate to follow is losing without any fight.}) 30.
Nh5+ {So is consistent with his attack.} ({There was an argument about the
pawn capture too:} 30. cxb4 Qd4 (30... Qe5 31. f4 {and White has both the
extra pawn and the attack.}) 31. Qxd4+ Bxd4 32. Bc4 Bd7 {Especially if one
could spot from afar the nice little tactic:} 33. b5 $1 cxb5 34. Bxb5 {that
undoubles the pawns and wins.}) 30... Kg6 {Suprisingly, this is not the best.}
({The slippery computer somehow avoids the mate in the line:} 30... Kh7 31. Bd3
Kg6 32. Nf4+ Kg7 33. e5 Qxc3 34. Nh5+ Kf8 35. Qxh6+ Ke7 36. Qf6+ Kd7) 31. Nf4+
Kh7 32. Nxe6 {Without this bishop, the end is almost here.} bxc3 (32... fxe6
33. Qxd6 {is hopeless obviously.}) 33. Qf4 fxe6 34. Qf7+ Kh8 35. Qf8+ Kh7 36.
e5 {Pffff! Just a move away from the win So slips!} ({But with a couple of
minutes on the clock it was impossible to calculate the following lengthy line:
} 36. Bd3 $1 Qd1 ({White's win is easier after:} 36... e5 37. Bc4 d5 38. exd5
Qe1 39. Bd3+) 37. Qxd6 c2 38. e5+ Kg7 39. Qe7+ Kg8 {First White is going to
clear the board from the opponent's pawns:} 40. Qxe6+ Kg7 41. Qg6+ Kf8 42.
Qxh6+ Kf7 43. Qf6+ {Then Whit will find a pawn to insert the bishop into the
attack:} Kg8 ({Or So may also promote his central pawn with:} 43... Ke8 44. e6
Qxd3 45. Qf7+ Kd8 46. e7+ Kc8 47. e8=Q+) 44. Bc4+ Kh7 45. Qf7+ Kh6 46. Qf8+ Kg6
47. Bf7+ {Once that the bishop is in, mate is inevitable:} Kf5 48. Bg8+ Kxe5
49. Qe7+ Kf5 50. Bh7+ Kf4 51. Qf6# {You have probably noticed that this main
line is fifteen moves long. And there were some sublines...}) 36... Qd1 {
The d3 square is covered, there is no more mate and Carlsen is suddenly out of
the woods!} 37. Qf7+ Kh8 38. Qe8+ Kh7 39. Qd7+ Kh8 40. Qc8+ Kg7 41. Qd7+ Kh8
42. Qe8+ Kg7 43. Qe7+ Kh8 44. Qxe6 {Frustrated, So keeps playing for a win but
now he will be the only one to risk.} Qd4 $1 {The world champion is taking his
chance at once.} ({Had he had wanted to force a draw, he would have opted for:
} 44... c2 45. Qxh6+ Kg8 46. Qg6+ {when perpetual is inevitable.}) 45. Qe8+ Kg7
46. Qe7+ Kg8 47. Qe6+ Kg7 48. Qf6+ Kh7 49. Qe7+ Kg8 50. Qe6+ Kg7 51. Qd7+ Kf8
52. Qf5+ Ke8 53. Qc8+ {And the king escapes from the checks.} ({Instead:} 53.
Qe6+ Kd8 54. Qg8+ Kc7 55. Qg7+ {Would have still forced perpetual as:} Kb8 {
is forced.} ({The attempt to block the checks with the bishop after:} 55... Kc8
$4 {Would have lost the game:} 56. Ba6+ Kd8 57. Qf8+ Kd7 58. e6+ Kxe6 59. Bc8+
Kd5 60. Qf5+ Qe5 61. Qf7+ Kd4 62. Qc4#) 56. Qf8+) 53... Ke7 54. exd6+ Qxd6 55.
Qf5 Qd4 {Centralization. The super-passer on c3 coupled with the threats that
Black create with his own pieces allows Carlsen a chance to squeeze So.} 56.
Qc2 Qg7+ 57. Kh1 Qe5 58. Bd3 Bc7 59. Kg2 Qh2+ 60. Kf1 Qxh3+ {A second passer
there is.} 61. Ke2 Qe6+ 62. Be4 Be5 63. Qa2 Qd6 64. Qa7+ Kf6 65. Qh7 Qd2+ 66.
Kf1 Bd4 {More pressure. Carlsen won a ton of games with his trademark grinding.
} 67. Qg6+ Ke7 68. Qg3 Bf6 $1 ({There is no time yet for:} 68... c2 69. Qc7+
Kf8 70. Qc8+ Kg7 71. Qc7+ {with a draw.}) 69. Qc7+ Qd7 70. Qf4 $1 ({Correctly
avoiding the pure opposite-coloured bishop endgame:} 70. Qxd7+ Kxd7 {when Black
has realistic winning chances thanks to his distant passers.}) 70... h5 {
Although the machines indicate that the position is still equal, it is evident
for a human that the only one who can play on is Black. White cannot hope for
anything other than a perpetual check.} 71. Qe3 Qd4 72. Qf4 Qd6 73. Qe3 c5 {
A bit more progress. It should have been extremely painful for So to suffer
like this after the won position he knew he had before.} 74. Bg6+ Kd8 75. Qe8+
Kc7 76. Be4 h4 77. Kg2 Qd7 78. Qh5 ({The computer suggests that:} 78. Qa8 Kb6
79. f4 {was best, with equality.}) 78... Kb6 79. f4 Qe6 80. Qg6 ({Here most
accurate was:} 80. Qh7 $1 {Not letting the black king in:} Ka5 81. Qa7+) 80...
Ka5 $1 {Now White's position gets close to critical.} 81. Bf5 Qd6 ({Missing
the strong:} 81... Qa6 $1 82. Qe8 Kb4 {Next the king will come to b2 and
even though there is no mathematical win yet, the practical chances that the
world champion has, coupled with his exceptional technique would have spelt
trouble for So.}) 82. Qe8 Kb6 83. Be4 Kc7 84. Qa8 Qxf4 85. Qc6+ Kd8 86. Qd5+
Ke8 87. Bg6+ Ke7 88. Qxc5+ {Maybe it was So who felt that the ending will be a
good one?} ({An instant draw was:} 88. Qb7+ Kd8 89. Qb6+ Kd7 90. Qb7+) 88...
Qd6 89. Qe3+ Kf8 $4 {And there it is! The decisive blunder.} ({Any other
reasonable move would have led to a draw:} 89... Kd7) ({Or:} 89... Qe5) ({Or:} 
89... Be5) 90. Qe8+ Kg7 91. Qf7+ Kh6 92. Qh7+ Kg5 93. Qh5+ {Mate is inevitable
and chess justice prevailed.} 1-0

