{[%evp 0,69,18,20,20,17,21,19,27,22,22,-10,18,18,7,6,15,-18,-10,-28,-7,-11,-9,
1,24,24,61,28,31,13,93,91,79,87,87,81,59,52,55,39,37,13,32,21,41,34,50,43,105,
77,70,72,67,62,71,67,224,215,242,221,226,220,217,260,440,374,439,447,487,472,
494,497]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3
d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. d5 {[%csl Ra5,Gd5]} Ne8 13. a4
c4 (13... Rb8 {is a concession which gives away the a-file. White can continue
with:} 14. axb5 axb5 {[%cal Ga1a8]} 15. Nbd2 (15. b3 {[%csl Ra5]}) 15... g6 16.
Nf1 Ng7 17. g4) 14. Nbd2 g6 {An inaccuracy.} ({The correct path to equality
here is actually:} 14... Rb8 $1 {[%cal Ga5b7,Gb7c5] Black abandons the a-file
but is ready to expel the annoying white pieces from there. The manoeuvre
Na5-b7-c5 would solve the problem of the Spanish knight too.} 15. Nf1 ({If:} 
15. b4 cxb3 16. Nxb3 Nxb3 17. Bxb3 Qxc3 18. Bd2 Qc7 19. axb5 axb5 20. Qe2 Bd8
$1 $11 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Rd8b6,Rb6g1] and the dark-squared bishop enters the
game.}) 15... g6 {[%cal Gc8d7,Ge8g7,Rf8a8] The communication between the black
pieces should be improved.} ({It is too early for:} 15... Nb7 16. axb5 axb5 17.
Ra7 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gc7b6,Rc1e3]}) 16. Bh6 Ng7 17. axb5 axb5 18. Ra3 Bd7 19.
Qa1 Nb7 20. Ra7 Qc8 {[%cal Ge7d8,Gd8b6,Gb7c5] The maneuver Be7-d8-b6 would
solve Black's issues.} 21. b4 (21. Ng3 Bd8 22. Qa6 Bc7 23. Be3 f5 24. exf5 gxf5
25. Bh6 Nc5 26. Qxc8 Rbxc8 $11) 21... cxb3 22. Bxb3 Nc5 23. Bc2 Bd8 {[%cal
Gd8b6,Gb8a8]}) 15. axb5 axb5 16. b4 cxb3 17. Nxb3 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gc2d3,Gd1e2,
Re2b5,Ga1b1,Gb1b2,Ge1b1] Now the pawn on b5 is an obvious target.} Bd7 18. Bd2
Ng7 {[%cal Ra5c4]} 19. Nxa5 Rxa5 20. Qe2 Rb8 21. Rab1 $1 {Notice that Adams
does not fight for the open file but rather prefers to use the rooks to attack
the isolated pawn.} Ra7 22. Bd3 Rab7 23. Rb4 Nh5 {The only chance to
compensate for the weakness is the active kingside counterplay.} ({After:} 
23... f5 24. exf5 Nxf5 (24... gxf5 25. Nd4 Bf6 26. Nxb5) 25. g4 Ng7 26. Reb1 {
[%csl Rb5] the pawn would be lost sooner or later.}) 24. Rc1 $1 {Another neat
rook move. White anticipates the opening of the c-file and places his rook
there in advance.} ({Black is holding after:} 24. Reb1 Nf4 (24... f5 25. exf5
gxf5 26. Nd4) 25. Bxf4 exf4 26. Qd2 (26. Bxb5 Bxb5 27. Rxb5 Rxb5 28. Rxb5 Rxb5
29. Qxb5 Qxc3 30. Qe8+ Bf8 31. Ng5 Qa1+ 32. Kh2 Qa7 (32... Qg7 {[%cal Gh7h6,
Gg7f6,Gf6d4]} 33. e5) 33. Nxh7 Qxf2 $11 {[%csl Rh2][%cal Rf2g3,Rf2e1]}) 26...
Bf6 27. Nd4 f3 $5 (27... Be5 28. Bxb5 Bxd4 29. Bxd7 Bc5 {[%cal Gc7e7,Ge7e5]}))
24... Bf6 25. Qd1 Qc8 26. Bf1 Bd8 27. c4 bxc4 {The decisive mistake.} ({
The only chance was:} 27... Ba5 {Although this is pretty grim after:} 28. cxb5
{And now both:} Qe8 ({And:} 28... Qd8 29. Rb3 Bxd2 30. Qxd2 (30. Nxd2 Bxb5 31.
Rcb1 $18) 30... Bxb5 31. Rcb1 Qd7 32. Qa5 Ba6 33. Rxb7 Rxb7 34. Rxb7 Bxb7 35.
Nd2 {[%cal Gd2c4,Ra5b6,Rf1b5]} Nf6 36. Qb6 Qe7 37. Bb5 Bc8 38. f3 Bd7 (38...
Bxh3 $1 39. gxh3 Nxd5 40. exd5 Qg5+ 41. Kf1 Qxd2 42. Qxd6 Qd1+ 43. Kg2 Qd2+ $11
) 39. Bc6) 29. Rb3 Bxd2 30. Nxd2 $1 (30. Qxd2 Bxb5 31. Rcb1 Ba6) 30... Bxb5 31.
Rcb1 Ba4 32. Rxb7 Rxb7 33. Qc1 Rxb1 34. Qxb1 Nf6 35. Nc4 Qe7 36. Qb4 Bc2 37. f3
{do not solve Black's problems. In the symmetrical position White's space
advantage as well as the weakness of the d6 pawn spell trouble for Black
indefinitely.}) 28. Rbxc4 Rc7 29. Rxc7 Bxc7 30. Nxe5 $1 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rd5d6]
} dxe5 31. d6 Bxd6 32. Rxc8+ Bxc8 33. Bg5 Bf8 34. Qd8 Ra8 35. Bc4 1-0

