{[%evp 0,145,18,20,17,33,31,21,28,-1,15,15,19,9,4,16,18,-9,-9,-17,-7,-7,-7,-7,
24,24,30,39,36,30,52,54,63,58,102,38,50,40,34,44,45,-36,-19,-20,-19,-28,-9,-23,
-6,-17,-16,-15,40,-6,14,-15,-15,-15,-8,-10,-7,-7,3,-25,-13,-22,-40,-61,-21,-55,
0,-61,-46,-85,0,0,0,0,26,21,35,8,8,-96,-90,-198,-198,-224,-91,-263,-100,-240,
-74,-69,-22,-141,-13,-20,6,16,47,-1,72,60,164,176,208,199,356,346,378,378,385,
384,403,359,358,347,589,555,597,594,608,589,657,581,29989,462,296,296,296,295,
295,295,350,350,338,362,372,366,366,380,394,404,434,438,477,492]} 1. e4 e5 2.
Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Na5
10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. d5 {With the closing of the centre White indicates
that he will attack on "his" kingside whereas Black needs to work in the
opposite direction. However, one of the problems that the second player is
often facing in these lines is his "Spanish knight". A problematic piece which
has difficulties entering the battle.} (12. Nbd2 Nc6 13. d5 {Still, a great
strategist of the past, Akiba Rubinstein managed to solve the problem of the
knight and found it a working place thanks to the following manoeuvre :} Nd8 14.
Nf1 Ne8 15. a4 Rb8 16. axb5 axb5 17. g4 g6 18. Ng3 Ng7 19. Kh1 f6 20. Rg1 Nf7 {
[%csl Gf7,Rg5,Gg7][%cal Gf7g5,Gf2f4,Re5f4,Rf7e5,Gg6g5,Gf7h8,Gh8g6,Gg6f4] The
knight is ready to hop on the g5 square. It both defends and attacks and is
ready to fill in a potential hole on e5 in case that White attacks with f2-f4.}
21. Qf1 Bd7 22. Be3 Ra8 23. Qg2 Rxa1 24. Rxa1 Qb7 25. Kh2 Ra8 26. Qf1 Ra6 27.
Nd2 Qa8 28. Rxa6 Qxa6 29. Nb3 Ng5 30. Kg2 h5 31. h4 Nf7 32. gxh5 gxh5 33. Kh2
Qc8 34. Qg2 Kf8 35. Nd2 f5 36. exf5 Bxh4 37. f6 Bxf6 38. Qf3 Bh4 39. Bg6 Bxg3+
40. fxg3 Bf5 41. Bxf7 Kxf7 42. Ne4 Qd7 43. Bh6 Kg6 44. Bxg7 Kxg7 45. b4 c4 46.
Nd2 Qf7 47. Qe3 Qxd5 48. Qg5+ Bg6 49. Qe7+ Kg8 50. Qd8+ Kf7 51. Qd7+ Kf6 52.
Qd8+ Kf5 53. Qd7+ Kf6 54. Qd8+ Kg7 55. Qe7+ Qf7 56. Qxd6 Qf2+ 57. Kh3 Kh6 58.
Nb1 Qf5+ 59. Kg2 Qxb1 60. Qf8+ Kg5 61. Qd8+ Kg4 62. Qd7+ Qf5 63. Qd1+ Kg5 {
0-1 (63) Thomas,G-Rubinstein, A Baden-Baden 1925}) 12... Bd7 13. b3 Nb7 14.
Nbd2 g6 {Luring the bishop on h6.} 15. Nf1 Nh5 16. Bh6 {[%csl Rh6] Now Black
will be able to chase this piece away with a tempo.} ({Black is doing fine
after:} 16. g4 Nf4 17. Bxf4 exf4 18. Qd2 Bf6 {[%csl Rc3,Gf6][%cal Rf6c3,Gb5b4]}
19. Rac1 Be5 {[%cal Gb7d6] as the knight is ready to occupy the d6 square if
needed.}) 16... Ng7 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gf7f6,Gb7d8,Gd8f7]} 17. g4 f6 18. Ng3 ({
There is no way to seal the queenside:} 18. a4 bxa4 (18... Rfb8 $5) 19. bxa4
Na5 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gb8b7,Gf8b8,Rc5c4]} 20. Ne3 Rfb8 21. c4 Rb4 {with counterplay.
}) 18... Nd8 19. Qd2 Nf7 {With a tempo. White needs to make a difficult
decision.} 20. Bxg7 ({Safer is:} 20. Be3 {Although here too, Black is doing
fine after:} c4 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Rc4b3,Rf8c8,Rc8c3]} (20... f5 21. exf5 gxf5
22. gxf5 {[%cal Gg1h2,Ge1g1,Rg1g2,Ra1g1]}) (20... h5 21. gxh5) 21. b4 a5 22. a3
Ra6 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gf8a8,Ra5b4]} (22... axb4 23. axb4 Qb7)) 20... Kxg7 {
[%cal Rc5c4] Now Black will prove superior as the dark-squared superiority
will become obvious on the long run.} 21. c4 Rfb8 {Keeps the pressure which is
favorable for Black.} ({It will be closer to equal after:} 21... bxc4 22. bxc4
Rfb8 23. Reb1) 22. Bd3 Rb7 23. Qc3 Bd8 $1 {[%csl Ga5][%cal Gd8a5] A standart
maneuver to bring the bishop out.} 24. Nd2 Qa5 25. Qc2 $17 ({The endgame after:
} 25. Qxa5 Bxa5 {[%csl Ga5] is clearly better for Black, for example:} 26. Red1
h5 27. f3 (27. gxh5 Ng5 {[%csl Rf3,Rh3][%cal Ra5d2,Rg5f3,Rg5h3]}) 27... hxg4
28. hxg4 Rh8 29. Kg2 Ng5 $19 {[%cal Gg5h3,Gh3f4,Ga5c3,Gc3d4,Rh8h7,Rb7b8,Rb8h8]}
) 25... h5 26. f3 Be7 27. Kg2 hxg4 28. fxg4 ({Or:} 28. hxg4 Rh8 29. Rh1 Rbb8
30. Rxh8 Rxh8 31. Rh1 Rxh1 32. Nxh1 Kg8 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Ge7f8,Gf8h6,Ra5a2,
Ga5e1]} 33. Nf2 Bf8 34. Nf1 Bh6 $17 {[%cal Gh6f4,Gf7g5,Gg8g7,Ra5d8,Rd8h8,Rh8h2,
Rh8h4] and Black's position will soon become won.}) 28... Rh8 $17 {Black is
better on both flanks. The dark squares are in his full control, White can
only sit and pray for his survival.} 29. Nf3 Rbb8 30. Rh1 Rh7 31. Qd2 Qc7 32.
Nf1 Kg8 33. Qf2 Qa5 34. Ne3 (34. Qd2 Qd8 {[%cal Ge7f8,Gf8h6,Rd8f6]}) 34... Qc3
35. Rhd1 Bf8 36. Nh4 Nh8 37. Kh2 Bh6 38. Nhg2 Kg7 39. Rac1 Qa5 40. Rc2 Nf7 41.
Rf1 Bg5 42. Rh1 Rbh8 (42... Rxh3+ 43. Kxh3 Rh8+ 44. Nh4 Bxh4 45. Qe2 (45. Qxh4
Rxh4+ 46. Kxh4) 45... Bg5+ 46. Kg2 Nh6 {[%csl Rg4]}) 43. Kg3 Qd8 {[%csl Rh3]
[%cal Gh7h6,Gh8h7,Gd8h8]} 44. Rcc1 Rh6 (44... Bxg4 45. Kxg4 (45. hxg4 Rxh1) (
45. Nxg4 Bxc1 46. Rxc1 Rxh3#) 45... Qd7+ 46. Kf3 Rxh3+ 47. Rxh3 Rxh3+ 48. Ke2
Nh6) 45. Rh2 f5 (45... Bxe3 $1 46. Nxe3 (46. Qxe3 Bxg4 47. Kxg4 Qd7+ 48. Kf3
Rxh3+ {[%csl Re3][%cal Rh3e3]}) 46... Ng5 47. h4 Rxh4 48. Rxh4 Rxh4 49. Kxh4
Qh8+ 50. Kg3 Qh3#) 46. exf5 (46. gxf5 Bf4+ 47. Nxf4 Qg5+ 48. Ng4 exf4+ 49. Kg2
Qxg4+) 46... e4 (46... Qf6 47. Be4 gxf5 48. Bxf5 e4 49. Bxd7 Qe5+ 50. Nf4 Bh4+)
47. fxg6 Rxg6 48. Bxe4 Rf6 (48... Qe7 49. Bxg6 Qe5+ 50. Kf3 Qxh2) 49. Bf5 (49.
Qb2 Qe7 (49... Re8)) 49... Bxf5 50. gxf5 Qe7 (50... Ne5 $1 {[%cal Gg7f8,Gh8g8]}
) 51. h4 Qe5+ 52. Nf4 Rfh6 53. Rch1 Bf6 54. Ng4 Qc3+ 55. Kg2 Bd4 56. Qe2 Ne5
57. Nxh6 Rxh6 58. Rh3 Qa5 59. Ne6+ Kf7 60. Rg3 bxc4 61. bxc4 Qa4 62. Qd2 Qxc4
63. Nxd4 cxd4 64. Qxh6 Qc2+ 65. Kg1 Qb1+ 66. Kh2 Qc2+ 67. Rg2 Ng4+ 68. Kg3
Qxg2+ 69. Kxg2 Nxh6 70. Kf3 Nxf5 71. h5 Kg7 72. Rg1+ Kh6 73. Ke4 1-0

