{[%evp 0,78,29,29,20,27,9,23,35,16,25,-24,-2,-16,-16,-16,-15,-29,-6,-5,16,12,
17,16,18,25,26,7,28,-1,0,-8,-8,-23,-28,-28,-31,-13,-9,-29,3,-50,-50,-35,-40,
-64,-59,-59,-45,-64,-29,-34,-37,-46,-46,-47,-47,-39,-10,-34,-34,-57,-57,-57,
-57,-128,-128,-128,-109,-140,-150,-150,-177,-165,-184,-184,-162,-144,-140,-198,
-141]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 {Carlsen follows the golden rule of the
experienced player- "an endgame with the youth".} 4. d3 {Rejected.} d6 5. c3 a6
6. Ba4 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 Re8 9. Nbd2 Bf8 10. h3 b5 11. Bc2 Bb7 12. d4 g6 {
Slowly the game shifted into the Zaitsev line.} 13. a3 ({Last-year Wijk
witnessed the following game:} 13. b3 d5 14. Bb2 exd4 15. cxd4 Nb4 16. e5 Nh5
17. a3 Nxc2 18. Qxc2 Nf4 19. b4 a5 20. Bc3 axb4 21. axb4 Rxa1 22. Rxa1 Bc8 {
L'Ami, E (2643)-Gledura, B (2615) Wijk aan Zee 2019}) 13... Nb8 {The knight is
moving to a better position, a'la Breyer, in order to free the light-squared
bishop.} 14. d5 c6 15. c4 Nbd7 {Black is doing fine out of the opening.
Firouzja's next move is a novelty.} 16. a4 $146 ({Black also did well in the
predecessor:} 16. b4 Nb6 17. dxc6 Bxc6 18. cxb5 axb5 19. Bb3 Bg7 20. Ra2 d5 {
[%csl Rd5][%cal Rd6d5]} 21. exd5 Nfxd5 {Shadrina,T (2416)-Kosintseva,T (2497)
St Petersburg 2009}) 16... Qc7 {Carlsen builds more pressure threatening to
open the files in a good moment.} 17. b3 {The first major thought by the
youngster.} ({He was probably debating on liquidation of the pressure. In the
line:} 17. dxc6 Bxc6 18. axb5 axb5 19. Rxa8 Rxa8 20. cxb5 Bxb5 21. Nb1 $5 {
[%csl Gd5][%cal Gb1c3,Gc3d5] White can try to control the center, but:} Qb7 22.
Nc3 Bc6 {[%csl Rb2,Rb7,Rc6,Rd5][%cal Rd6d5,Rb7b2] promises Black the better
control when the b2 pawn might easily become vulnerable.}) 17... Rec8 18. Ra2 (
{More natural seems:} 18. Bb1 bxc4 19. bxc4 {Althoguh Black is more than fine
after:} Nc5 {[%csl Gc5]} ({Or as in the game:} 19... a5 $5 {[%csl Ga6][%cal
Gb7a6]})) 18... bxc4 19. bxc4 a5 20. Nf1 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Rf1g3,Rg6h5,Rg6f5]
Strangely enough, this is a mistake. The knight cannot find good position for
itself on the kingside.} ({Correct was:} 20. Nb1 $1 {[%csl Gb1,Gb5][%cal Gb1a3,
Ga3b5] Anticipating:} Ba6 21. Na3 cxd5 22. cxd5 Rab8 23. Bd2 {[%csl Gc2][%cal
Ga3c2,Ga3b5]}) 20... Ba6 21. Ne3 ({Black is better after:} 21. N3d2 Rab8 22.
Ne3 cxd5 23. cxd5 Qc3 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Gb8b1,Gc8c1,Ga6f1,Gf8h6]}) 21... Nc5 {
Simply bringing more pieces into the game.} ({The same could have been done
with:} 21... Rab8 22. dxc6 Qxc6 23. Nd2 Bh6 {[%cal Gh6c1]}) 22. Nd2 {Firouzja
hesitates and this makes his position even worse. Carlsen still has pieces to
bring out and improve his situation further.} ({It made sense to open some
room for his piecs with:} 22. dxc6 Qxc6 23. Nd5 {[%csl Gd5]} Ncd7 24. Nd2 {
Then:} Bxc4 ({However, Black can preserve the advantage with:} 24... Rab8 $1 {
[%csl Rc4]}) 25. Nxc4 Qxc4 26. Nxf6+ Nxf6 27. Bb3 {[%csl Rd5,Gf7,Gg8][%cal
Gb3g8] promises White ample compensation on the light squares.}) 22... cxd5
23. cxd5 Rab8 24. Ba3 Qd8 {[%cal Gd8f6] Brings the queen to a better position
too.} (24... Nh5 $5 {[%cal Gh5f4] made good sense too.}) 25. Qf3 h5 {[%cal
Gf8h6] The bishop's turn it is.} 26. Raa1 Bh6 27. Rab1 ({Or:} 27. Rec1 Kg7 {
[%cal Gh5h4,Gh6f4,Rd8h8,Rh8h6,Rh6g5,Gf6h5] followed by h5-h4 and Bh6-f4 in a
good moment.}) 27... Rxb1 $1 {The world champion is OK to trade, but just one
rook. The other one will have a career soon.} 28. Rxb1 Kg7 (28... Bf4 $5 {
was not bad neither.}) 29. Nef1 {White's position gets worse by the move, but
it is difficult to give him an advise.} ({Still, better was:} 29. Ndf1 {
With the idea to meet:} h4 30. Ng4) 29... h4 30. Ne3 Bf4 31. Nef1 ({Or:} 31.
Ndf1 Nd3 $1 {[%csl Gd3] with quick collapse.}) 31... Qc7 (31... Nh7 $1 {
[%csl Rf3][%cal Gh7g5] would be great too.}) 32. g3 {After this, the game is
quickly over.} ({But:} 32. Re1 {should not have saved White neither, either
because of:} Nh7 $1 ({Or because of:} 32... Nb7 $1 33. Bd3 Bxd3 34. Qxd3 Qc3))
32... hxg3 33. fxg3 Bh6 34. h4 ({If:} 34. Kg2 Qa7 $1 {[%cal Ra7g1] would
activate the black queen.}) 34... Qd7 {[%csl Ra4] Simply winning a pawn.
Carlsen's play was amazingly simple and effective!} 35. Kg2 Nxa4 36. Bxa4 Qxa4
37. Bxd6 Qd4 38. Qf2 ({Or:} 38. Nb3 Rc2+) 38... Qxf2+ 39. Kxf2 Bxf1 ({Firouzja
resigned due to the line:} 39... Bxf1 40. Kxf1 Bxd2 41. Bxe5 Bc3 42. Rc1 Bxe5
43. Rxc8 Bxg3) 0-1

