1. e4 c5 {Yes, it starts as Sicilian, but it will soon be Ruy Lopez.} 2. Nf3 d6
3. Bb5+ Nc6 4. O-O Bd7 5. c3 Nf6 6. Re1 a6 7. Ba4 b5 (7... c4 8. Na3 ({
Engaging in the battle of strategies White comes up with the idea of b2-b3
trying to force the exchange of the black c-pawn for its flank counterpart 
(with the same end in view to obtain the pawn majority in the centre). To make
this move possible he should withdraw the bishop to avoid its loss after b7-b5.
Playing White against Avrukh in Israel 2002 Smirin did it at once -} 8. Bc2 e5
(8... Bg4 {is playable as well}) 9. b3 cxb3 10. axb3 Bg4 11. d3 Be7 12. Nbd2
O-O 13. h3 Bh5 14. Nf1 d5 15. g4 Bg6 16. Ng3 {with double-edged play. Shortly
after we will see the idea behind White's clumsy 8th move}) 8... b5 9. Bc2 Bg4
(9... e6 10. b3 cxb3 11. axb3 Be7 12. d4 b4 13. d5 $1 bxa3 14. dxc6 Bxc6 15.
Bxa3 {Tseitlin - Olafsson, Palma de Mallorca 1989 with White's edge in both
cases}) 10. h3 Bh5 ({The course of the game showed that} 10... Bxf3 11. Qxf3
Ne5 12. Qe2 e6 13. b3 Qc7 {is preferable trying to keep the pawn on c4}) 11. b3
cxb3 ({Now} 11... Ne5 {is met with} 12. g4 Bg6 (12... Nfxg4 $2 {fails to} 13.
Nxe5) 13. bxc4 $1 ({stronger than} 13. Nxe5 cxb3 $1 14. axb3 dxe5) 13... Nxc4
14. Nxc4 bxc4 15. Ba4+ Nd7 16. d4 cxd3 17. Qxd3 {when White's lead in
development determines his advantage.}) 12. axb3 e5 13. d4 ({This advance
could be prepared by} 13. Bb2 {but after} Be7 14. d4 O-O 15. d5 Na7 {the
dark-squared bishop would have been misplaced. Actually White doesn't need any
preparation.}) 13... Be7 14. d5 Na7 15. Bd3 $16 {[%csl Ra6,Rb5][%cal Gf1a6]}
Qc7 16. Bd2 (16. Nb1 $5 {[%csl Ra6] attacking the a6 pawn without delay and
intending to put the bishop on e3}) 16... O-O 17. Qe2 Nd7 18. b4 {[%csl Ra6,
Ra7,Gb4,Rb5]} Nb6 19. g4 Bg6 20. Ra2 Rfe8 21. Nh2 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4]
Profilaxis.} (21. Rea1 Nxd5 $1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Re5e4]}) 21... Rec8 22. Rea1 h6
23. Nb1 {[%csl Ra6]} Na4 24. Bc2 Bg5 25. Be1 f6 26. Bb3 Qb7 27. Nf1 Rc7 28. Ng3
Nc8 29. Bxa4 bxa4 30. Rxa4 {[%csl Ra6]} Be8 31. Ra5 Bb5 32. Qf3 Nb6 33. Na3 Be8
34. Nf5 Rd8 35. Qd3 g6 36. Ng3 Ra8 37. f3 h5 38. Bf2 Bf4 39. Ne2 hxg4 40. hxg4
Rh7 41. Nxf4 exf4 42. Kg2 Rh6 43. Rh1 Rxh1 44. Kxh1 Kf7 45. Kg2 Bd7 46. Qd2 g5
47. c4 Bxg4 48. fxg4 Nd7 49. Bd4 Rh8 50. c5 $4 (50. b5 $18) 50... dxc5 51. Bxc5
$4 (51. Nc4 Qb8 52. Bg1) 51... Ne5 52. Bg1 Qc8 53. Kf1 Nf3 54. Qe2 Qxg4 55. Qg2
Nh2+ 56. Bxh2 Qd1+ 57. Kf2 f3 58. Qg1 Qe2+ 59. Kg3 Rh4 60. Qf2 Rh3+ {0-1 (60)
Bojkov,D (2445)-Wojtaszek,R (2622) Ermioni GRE 2006}) 8. Bc2 e5 ({or choose} 
8... Bg4 {e.g.} 9. d3 (9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 g6) 9... e6 10. Nbd2 Be7 11. h3 Bh5
12. Nf1 Nd7 13. Ng3 Bg6 {as Dreev played against Svetushkin at the recent
Moscow Open}) 9. h3 Be7 10. d4 O-O 11. d5 Na5 {Now we are in the Ruy Lopez
territory.} 12. Nbd2 Qc7 13. b3 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gb3c4] Limiting the
problematic knight.} c4 14. b4 Nb7 {[%csl Yb7]} 15. Nf1 a5 16. Ng3 axb4 17.
cxb4 g6 {[%csl Yb5,Yc4]} 18. Bh6 Rfc8 19. a3 {[%csl Rb5] The b5+c4 pawn pair
is fixed, and the knight on b7 lacks any perspectives on the queenside. In
these situations, the c4 passer is not dangerous. Anytime it moves it falls
prey to the white active pieces. Therefore, Black can only wait on the
queenside and it is White who is attacking the fixed pawn pair.} Nd8 20. Nd2 $1
{[%csl Rb5][%cal Gd2b1,Gb1c3,Gc3b5] Heading towards the b5 pawn.} Ne8 21. Nb1
Ra6 22. Nc3 Rca8 23. Bc1 f6 24. Rb1 Nf7 25. Qe2 Bd8 26. a4 {[%csl Rc4] Even if
the pawns are traded White's initiative will remain. The main problem is with
the weak d6 pawn.} bxa4 27. b5 {[%csl Ra4] Separates the black pawns which
will not survive.} Ra5 28. Ba3 Rc8 29. Nf1 Qb7 30. Nd2 Bxb5 31. Nxb5 {Forcing
a pin.} ({The white pieces are vulnerable in case of:} 31. Bxa4 Nc7 32. Nxc4
Bxc4 33. Qxc4 Qa6 34. Qxa6 (34. Qc6 Ra8 35. Rb6) 34... Nxa6) 31... Rxb5 32.
Bxa4 Rxb1 33. Rxb1 Bb6 ({More resilient was:} 33... Qa7 34. Bxe8 Qxa3 35. Qg4
Rc7 36. Bxf7+ Rxf7 (36... Kxf7 37. Nxc4 Rxc4 38. Qd7+) 37. Nxc4 $16 {althoguh
White is significantly better here too.}) 34. Bc6 Qa6 35. Nxc4 Bd4 36. Rb4 {
[%csl Ra6][%cal Rb4a4,Ra4a6]} Rxc6 37. dxc6 Qxc6 38. Rb8 Kg7 39. Ne3 Ba7 40.
Rb4 Nc7 41. Qc4 Qxc4 42. Nxc4 Bc5 43. Rb7 Bxa3 44. Nxa3 Ne6 45. Nb5 Nc5 46. Ra7
Nxe4 47. f3 Neg5 48. h4 Ne6 49. Nxd6 Ned8 50. Ne8+ 1-0

