{[%evp 0,93,18,31,31,25,18,15,65,-3,14,4,64,69,31,44,39,-17,-6,-4,7,0,17,24,24,
23,36,32,30,30,30,30,29,38,33,36,31,23,28,33,58,12,33,25,44,18,45,44,39,39,40,
17,26,-13,0,8,-44,-7,-17,-5,28,2,57,52,74,63,63,34,22,19,19,56,0,-13,-21,-102,
-67,0,31,31,43,79,297,7,35,0,0,-65,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,0]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
(3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. O-O h6 7. Re1 O-O 8. Nbd2 a5 {Nakamura is
the main proponent of this line against the Italian. He has running
mini-matches against Ding, Carlsen, and So.} 9. Nf1 Be6 10. Bb5 Bb6 11. Ng3 {
[#]} Nh7 $146 {A novelty.This idea is mostly seen in the lines where the black
bishop stands on e7. Here too, it is possible and aims to better control of
the d4 square.} 12. h3 Ng5 13. Nxg5 ({Normally White would like to keep more
pieces on board, but:} 13. Nh2 Qf6 {Allows Black too much activity.}) 13...
hxg5 {[%csl Rg5,Rg7][%cal Gg3f5,Gh3h4]} 14. d4 {So breaks through the centre
anyway.} ({Black is not afraid of:} 14. Qh5 f6) 14... exd4 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16.
cxd4 c5 {Black is trying to clarify the central situation, but this leads to
problems.} ({Instead:} 16... f6 $5 {looks safer, with a possible line:} 17. d5
cxd5 18. exd5 Bf7 19. Be3 {where White is only a tad better.}) 17. d5 Bd7 18.
a4 $1 {[%csl Rb6] An important move that keeps the black dark-squared bishop
locked.} ({After:} 18. Qf3 a4 $1 19. Bd2 Ba5 {Black is in time to bring his
problematic piece into life.}) 18... Re8 ({The bishop cannot be saved for free:
} 18... c4 19. Be3 {practically loses the c4 pawn for Black.}) ({However:} 
18... Qf6 {was more active. Then:} 19. Qh5 ({Therefore So might have chosen
instead:} 19. Qc2 Rfe8 20. Ra3) ({Or the immediate rook lift:} 19. Ra3 Qg6 {
with chances for a kingside attack.}) 19... c4 20. Re2 Rab8 {promises Black
counterplay.}) 19. Bd2 c4 {Nakamura is OK to sacrifice the pawn after all.} 20.
Qf3 Rb8 21. Bc3 Bc5 $1 {[%cal Gc5b4] As the bishop really needs out.} 22. Re2
$1 {[%csl Re1][%cal Rb4e1,Ge2b2] Prevents the trade.} ({Naturally not:} 22.
Bxa5 Rxb2) 22... f6 ({As:} 22... Bb4 {will be met with:} 23. Bd4) ({Black
likely did not like:} 22... Rb3 {due to the strong maneuver:} 23. Nf1 $1 {
Threatening Nf1-d2xc4, but here he could have created sudden counterplay with:}
g4 $5 24. hxg4 Qg5 25. Ne3 Bb4 {with compensation for the pawn.}) 23. Nf5 {
So is in control and has various attacking ideas on stock.} Bb4 ({After:} 23...
Bxf5 {White likely planned:} 24. exf5 $1 {[%csl Rc4,Ge6][%cal Ge2e6] With the
intention to slam a rook on e6, or at least to win the c4 pawn:} Rxe2 25. Qxe2
Qc8 26. g4) 24. Bd4 {This obvious move allows Black a sudden chance.} ({
More accurate was:} 24. Ne3 $5 Bxc3 25. bxc3 c6 26. Rd2 cxd5 27. Rxd5 {with
serious advantage for the first player. So will come back to his plan a bit
later.}) 24... Bc5 ({Stronger was:} 24... Bxf5 25. exf5 Rxe2 26. Qxe2 Qc8 {
Since the move:} 27. g4 (27. Qxc4 Qxf5) {Can be strongly met with:} 27... c5 $1
) 25. Bc3 Bb4 26. Ne3 {Back to the plan from above. The c4 pawn is doomed.} Bc8
27. Bd4 {So wants to extract the maximum from the position.} ({Apparently
Nakamura was hoping for the blockade after:} 27. Nxc4 Ba6 28. b3 ({But here
too White would be better after:} 28. Nxa5 $5 Bxe2 29. Qxe2 Bxa5 30. Bxa5)
28... Bxc4 29. bxc4 Bxc3 30. Qxc3 Rb4) 27... Ba6 28. Nf5 Bc8 29. Ne3 {Black's
position is extremely suspicious to say at least.} (29. Rc1 {at once was good
too.}) 29... Ba6 30. Nf5 Bc8 ({The computer's suggestion as the best defence is:
} 30... c3 {when Black might have feared either the positional exchange
sacrifice:} 31. bxc3 ({Or the simple:} 31. Rc2 cxb2 32. Rxb2) 31... Bxe2 32.
Qxe2 Bc5 33. Qh5) 31. Rc1 {at once was good too.} Qd7 {This attempt for a
counterplay loses instantly, but Black lacks good advise. The white pieces
keep coming closer to his king, h3-h4 is due to happen sooner or later.} ({
Instead:} 31... Bxf5 32. Qxf5 c3 33. bxc3 Bc5 {is hopeless too.}) 32. Rec2 Ba6
({There is no time for:} 32... Qxa4 33. Nxg7 $1) 33. h4 $1 {The inevitable
happened. Black's king is due to be mated.} gxh4 34. Qg4 {Threatens Nf5-h6+.}
Kf8 ({Even easier is White's play after:} 34... Kh8 35. Qxh4+ Kg8 36. Qg4) 35.
Bxf6 $3 {Without any hesitation. So discovers the enemy king as he knows he
has enough time to bring his pieces to support the queen and the knight.} gxf6
36. Qxh4 ({The other way to attack was:} 36. Qh5 Qf7 37. Qh8+ Qg8 38. Qxf6+ Qf7
39. Qh6+ Kg8 40. Qg5+ Kf8 41. Nh6) 36... Kg8 37. Re2 Re5 ({Alas, Black cannot
bring his defender in:} 37... Re7 38. Re3 Rg7 39. Nxg7) ({Neither does the
control of he third rank help:} 37... Bc5 38. Rc3 Rb3 {As White can switch to
the winning line from above with:} 39. Qg4+ Kf8 40. Qh5 Kg8 41. Qg6+ Kf8 42.
Qxf6+ Qf7 43. Qh6+ Kg8 44. Qg5+ Kf8 45. Nh6) 38. Re3 Rxf5 39. Rh3 Rg5 ({Or:} 
39... Qg7 40. exf5) 40. Qh8+ Kf7 41. Rh7+ {Black resigned as mate is
unstoppable. 1-0 (41) So,W (2741)-Nakamura,H (2829) Skilling Open | Knockout
2020 [Bojkov,Dejan]} (41. Rh7+ Kg6 42. Rh6+ Kf7 43. Qxf6+ Ke8 44. Rh8+)) 3...
g6 4. c3 a6 5. Ba4 d6 6. d4 Bd7 7. O-O Bg7 8. h3 Nf6 9. Re1 O-O 10. Nbd2 Re8
11. d5 ({Another continuation is:} 11. Bc2 b5 12. Nf1 Na5 13. Ng3 c5 14. d5 Nc4
15. b3 Nb6 16. Bg5 h6 17. Be3 a5 18. Qd2 Kh7 19. Kh1 {which led to lengthy
maneuvering in Maghsoodloo,P (2676)-Sjugirov,S (2675) chess.com INT 2020})
11... Ne7 12. Bc2 {[#]} Bh6 $146 {A typical idea to trade the potentially bad
bishop which turns out to be a novelty.} ({The predecessor saw:} 12... h6 13.
Nf1 Nh7 14. g4 f5 15. gxf5 gxf5 16. exf5 Bxf5 17. Bxf5 Nxf5 18. Ng3 Qd7 19. Kh2
{Tokhirjonova,G (2378)-Safarli,E (2598) Europe Chess INT 2020}) 13. Nf1 {
Nepomniachtchi is fine with the trade as the weakened dark kingside squares
might tell on the long run.} Bxc1 14. Qxc1 Kg7 15. Ng3 ({If White wanted to
avoid the next resource, he could have started with:} 15. Qd2 $5) 15... a5 {
Not only to arrange the pawns in the "proper way", and slow down White's
queenside expansion.} ({Since there is no pressure along the d-file Artemiev
could have played:} 15... c6 $5 {Apparently, both came to the conclusion that
White is somewhat better after:} 16. dxc6 Bxc6 17. Qd2 Qc7 18. Rad1) 16. c4 Qb8
$5 {The famous Rubinstein manoeuvre. Artemiev brings the queen in the game.} ({
Here:} 16... c6 {can be met with:} 17. dxc6 Nxc6 18. Rd1 Qc7 19. Ba4 $5 ({
Less good is:} 19. Qd2 Nb4)) 17. b3 Qa7 18. Bd3 Qc5 {The queen is out, but how
strong she is there?} 19. a3 ({A tad more accurate seems:} 19. Qb2 $5 {in
order to meet:} c6 {with:} 20. Rac1) 19... c6 {Finally opting for this move.}
20. dxc6 bxc6 ({White is a little better after:} 20... Nxc6 21. Qd2 Nd4 22.
Nxd4 Qxd4 23. Red1) 21. Qd2 {Hitting the d6 weakness, just in case.} ({More
natural seems:} 21. Qc3 {with the idea:} Be6 22. b4 Qb6 23. c5) 21... Be6 22.
b4 {Little by little Nepomniachtchi forces the queen back home.} axb4 23. axb4
Qb6 24. Bf1 Qc7 25. Qc3 {Back to the ideal spot.} ({The play for an outside
passer with:} 25. b5 Rxa1 26. Rxa1 {Yield White nothing after:} Rb8) ({
Likewise:} 25. Rad1 Red8 {is solid for Black.}) 25... Nd7 {Just in time to
defend the e5 pawn. Artemiev's position is passive, but super-solid.} 26. Rad1
f6 27. Rd2 c5 {This was not timely.} ({Instead some play along the open a-file
made sense:} 27... Ra4 28. Red1 Nc8 29. Qb3 Qa7 {with dynamical equality 
(Ra4-a3 followed by Be6xh3 ideas are already in the air).}) 28. b5 {Now Black
will lack a move to generate threats.} Nb6 29. Red1 Red8 30. Be2 $1 {A far
stronger move than it seems! The bishop vacates the f1 square for the knight
which is heading towards the d5 square, gets ready to show itself on the h3-g4
diagonal. And if this was too little for you- Nepomniachtchi sets a devilish
trap in the process.} Rd7 ({The obvious attacking move:} 30... Ra4 {Would have
walked into the trap:} 31. Nxe5 $1 {Wins material as the Rd8 lacks defence.
And if:} fxe5 32. Rxd6 $1) ({White is not disturbed by:} 30... Na4 31. Qc2) 31.
Nf1 Nec8 {Resigning to passive defence.} ({White is just in time now:} 31...
Ra4 32. Ne3) 32. Ne3 {[%csl Ge3] Nepomniachtchi's next moves are preparing
a powerful attack.} Qb8 33. Nh4 Ra4 34. Bg4 $1 {[%csl Re6,Rf5] Trading the weaker
bishop.} Bxg4 35. hxg4 Qa8 {Artemiev does not feel the danger.} ({Something
solid-like:} 35... Rf7 $5 {should have been preferred.}) 36. g5 $1 {After the
perfect preparation, the time had come for the tactical blows.} fxg5 37. Nhf5+
$3 {[%csl Rf5,Rg7] The point which forces the black king to further weaken
itself.} ({Worse is:} 37. Nef5+ {As it allows an additional chance to Black:}
Kf8 38. Nxd6 Nxd6 39. Rxd6 Rxd6 40. Rxd6 Qxe4 {when it is anyone's game.})
37... gxf5 ({This time the retreat does not make sense:} 37... Kg8 38. Nxd6)
38. Nxf5+ Kg8 {Obviously both players were playing by ear as there was not
enough time to calculate lines and even if there were, it would have been
close to impossible to calculate till the end.} ({The better defense:} 38...
Kf8 {Might not have saved Black either, although the attacking line is far
from trivial:} 39. Qe3 Ra1 {Trading the potential attacker.} ({If:} 39... h6
40. Qh3 $1 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gh3h6]} Rh7 41. Nxd6 Nxd6 42. Rxd6 {[%cal Rd6d8]}
Ra1 43. Qf5+ Rf7 44. Qe6 Rxd1+ 45. Rxd1 {and Black's positon collapses.}) 40.
Qxg5 Rxd1+ 41. Rxd1 Qxe4 42. Qf6+ Ke8 43. Qh8+ Kf7 {Perpetual there is, but is
there anything more:} 44. Qxh7+ Kf6 (44... Ke6 45. Qg6#) 45. Qh6+ $3 {[%csl
Rh6] Yes, there is a sudden mating net in the middle of the board!} Kxf5 46. f3
$3 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Rg2g4] That is revealed by this silent move. In order to
avoid mate Black needs to part with the queen:} Qd4+ 47. Rxd4 exd4 48. g4+ Ke5
49. Kf2 $1 {The computer claims that White is winning, although it does not
seem clear to me.}) 39. Qg3 Qxe4 40. Qxg5+ Kf7 41. Rd3 {Nepomniachtchi tried
to bring the rook in the attack, and this misses the win!} ({Missing the
brilliancy from above:} 41. Qg7+ $1 Ke6 (41... Ke8 42. Qg8#) 42. Qh6+ $3 Kxf5 {
And now:} 43. f3 $1 {is even stronger than from above and wins for certain.})
41... Ra1 $3 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Re4d3,Ra1g1] Brilliant defense in return!} 42.
Rxa1 Qxd3 43. Ra3 {Not necessary.} ({This time there is no:} 43. Qg7+ Ke6 44.
Qh6+ Kxf5 45. f3 Qd4+ {and Black wins.}) ({White could have forced a darw at
once with:} 43. Nh6+ Ke6 44. Qg4+ Kf6 45. Ng8+ Kf7 46. Nh6+) 43... Qxa3 44.
Nh6+ Ke8 45. Qg8+ Ke7 46. Qg5+ Ke6 47. Qf5+ {It is perpetual, but the
unthinkable happened at this point of the game- Artemiev got disconnected and
lost the game at once!} 1-0

