Nc4 f6 {[#]} 10. Rb1 $5 $146 {A novelty which intends to dispatch the black
bishop from the a7-g1 diagonal.} ({The predecessor was an email game which saw:
} 10. c3 a5 11. Ne3 Bxe3 12. Bxe3 Qe7 13. Qb3 Bxf3 14. gxf3 b6 15. Qc4 Qd6 16.
d4 {with unclear play, Cruzado Duenas,C (2602)-Almiron,L (2598) ICCF email 2012
}) 10... a5 $1 {Carlsen wants his bishop on the diagonal.} ({White's play is
easier after:} 10... O-O 11. b4 Be7 12. a3 ({Or:} 12. Ne3)) 11. Bd2 b6 12. Be3
Be7 {Now that the e3 square is occupied by the white bishop, Black can retreat.
} ({Although there was nothing wrong with:} 12... Bxe3 13. Nxe3 Nc5 {followed
by Nc5-e6.}) 13. b3 {White is arranging his pawns according to the
Capablanca's rule- on the opposite colour of his own bishop. Make no mistake
though- this is purely defensive here as they are not moving anywhere.} ({If:} 
13. a3 a4 {would prevent White from making any progress on the queenside.})
13... Nc5 {Carlsen wants to occupy the d4 square in the most convenient way.} (
{Once again Black had a reasonable alternative:} 13... c5 $5 {Followed by
either Nd7-b6-c6 or Nd7-f8-e6 on route to the d4 square.}) 14. a4 Ne6 15. Qe2
c5 16. c3 $1 {Firouzja needs to change the trend. If he stays, he will be
slowly smothered.} Qd7 17. Rfd1 Rd8 ({It makes no sense to castle into it:} 
17... O-O-O {As:} 18. b4 $1 cxb4 19. d4 $1 {would seize the initiative for
White:} ({Also interesting is:} 19. Bxb6 bxc3 {Although it is less clear.})
19... Bxf3 20. gxf3 exd4 21. cxd4 {With strong threats for White.}) 18. Rb2 Qc8
19. Rbd2 {White is consistent with the preparation of the d3-d4 break. Indeed,
there is nothing else that he can play for.} O-O ({One more prophylaxis:} 19...
Qb7 $5 {made sense too. Black hits the e4 pawn, thus preventing the d3-d4
break.}) 20. g4 Bf7 21. Nh4 ({It is too early for:} 21. d4 cxd4 22. cxd4 exd4
23. Nxd4 Nxd4 24. Rxd4 Rxd4 25. Rxd4 Rd8 {with pleasant endgame for Black
thanks to the bishop pair.}) 21... g6 22. Ng2 g5 $1 {Carlsen is stopping the
other typical break for White, f2-f4.} 23. f3 h5 24. Bf2 Kh7 {In order to
bring occupy the h-file before opening it.} (24... Nf4 $5 25. Nxf4 exf4 {
deserved serious investigation as well.}) 25. Nce3 {Active play.} ({Firouzja
could have prepared for the assault with:} 25. Qf1 Rh8 26. Nge3) 25... Rh8 26.
Nf5 Bf8 {Now that the black pieces are awkwardly placed, the moment should be
right:} 27. d4 {Changing the rhythm of the game when even world champions may
err.} cxd4 28. cxd4 hxg4 ({Black could have preserved his advantage with:} 
28... exd4 $1 29. Nxd4 Bb4 30. Nxe6 Rxd2 31. Nxg5+ fxg5 32. Rxd2 Bxd2 33. Qxd2
Qd8 {Black's king is not great, but an exchange is an exchange.}) 29. hxg4 Bb4
{A blunder!} ({It was not too late for:} 29... Nxd4 30. Nxd4 exd4 31. Bxd4 Bxb3
{when Black would be better.}) 30. d5 $1 {A nasty reversal.} Ng7 ({In the line:
} 30... Bxd2 {Carlsen might have missed the zwischen-zug:} 31. dxe6 $1 Qxe6 32.
Rxd2 Qxb3 {but from hindsight this might have been Black's best chance under
the circumstances.}) 31. Rc2 Nxf5 32. gxf5 Qd7 33. Ne3 {Now that a file has
been opened for the white rooks, and an outpost cleared for the white knight
it all starts to make perfect sense for White. In fact, he is strategically
winning.} Kg7 34. Rdc1 Rc8 35. Rc6 Rh3 ({Black should have defended passively
instead:} 35... Bd6) 36. Kg2 Rch8 37. Ng4 {Solid, there is no time to check
the tactical nuances.} ({However, the pawn was edible:} 37. Rxc7 $1 {The rooks
do not have enough energy to create mating threats:} Rh2+ 38. Kf1 Rh1+ 39. Bg1
Qd8 40. Qa6 {And whenever Black tries to add more attackers:} Bc5 {There is:}
41. R1xc5 $1 bxc5 42. Qb7 Qe8 43. Ng4 {and Black is helpless.}) 37... Bd6 38.
Bg3 ({The right plan was to go for the c7 pawn at once:} 38. Qc2 $1 Qe7 39.
Rxc7 Bxc7 40. Qxc7 Qxc7 41. Rxc7 {and Black's position crumbles.}) 38... R3h7
39. Qb2 {Firouzja knows the plan, but wastes some moves in executing it.} ({
It was not too late for:} 39. Qc4 {As:} Rc8 {does not help due to:} 40. Rxb6 $1
) 39... Qe7 40. R1c4 {Ooops, a blunder.} Bh5 (40... Be8 $1 {would have trapped
the white rook.}) 41. Qc3 Bxg4 42. Rxc7 $1 {Just in time! Now the forcing line:
} ({After:} 42. fxg4 Kg8 {Black defends, at least for the time being.}) 42...
Bh3+ 43. Kf2 Bxc7 44. Rxc7 Kh6 45. Rxe7 Rxe7 {Leads to a won position for
White as Firouzja keeps on playing energetically:} 46. d6 Rd7 47. Bxe5 $1 {
And brings his pawns into motion.} fxe5 48. Qxe5 Kh7 49. Qf6 ({Had White had
removed the bishop out of the way with:} 49. Kg3 $1 Bf1 50. f6 {the result
would have been different.}) 49... Rg8 $1 50. e5 ({Once more:} 50. Kg3 Bf1 51.
Qe6 {was the most convincing win.}) 50... Rgg7 {Carlsen managed to gather the
remnants of his army.} 51. Kg3 Rdf7 {O, horror! The most important passer is
about to fall.} 52. Qd8 {And does fall after this move.} ({Firouzja actually
spotted the correct idea:} 52. Qxf7 $3 Rxf7 53. e6 Rxf5 54. d7 {But missed
that after:} Rd5 {He has the winning:} 55. Kxh3 $1) 52... Bxf5 53. Qe8 {
Now tables are turned in Black's favour.} ({Instead:} 53. Qxb6 g4 54. Qxa5 gxf3+
55. Kxf3 {would have been completely unclear.}) 53... Bd7 54. Qa8 Rg6 55. Qb7
Re6 56. Qe4+ Kg7 57. Qe3 Rf5 ({The other idea was to play for a mate with:} 57...
g4 $1 58. fxg4 Rg6) 58. Qxb6 Rexe5 59. Qa7 Rf7 60. Qd4 Kf6 61. b4 axb4 62. Qxb4
({The last chance was:} 62. a5 $1 {Although there too, Black should win with:}
Rh7 63. a6 Rh3+ 64. Kg2 Rh4 65. Qb2 b3 $1 66. Qxb3 Ra4) 62... Kg6 63. a5 Re3 {
The united Black pieces reach the white king and it was soon over:} 64. a6
Rexf3+ 65. Kg2 Rf2+ 66. Kg1 Rf1+ 67. Kg2 Bc6+ 68. Kg3 R7f3+ 69. Kh2 R3f2+ 70.
Kg3 Rg2+ {0-1 (70) Firouzja,A (2728)-Carlsen,M (2863) St. Louis Rapid & Blitz
2020 [Bojkov,Dejan]}) 6... Be6 7. O-O (7. Nb3 Bb6 8. Qe2 Nd7 9. Be3 Qe7 10.
Nfd2 O-O-O 11. a4 Bxe3 12. Qxe3 Kb8 13. a5 g6 14. O-O f5 15. exf5 gxf5 16. f4 {
Nakamura, H (2736) -Firouzja, A (2728) chess.com INT 2020}) 7... Bd6 ({Just a
few days ago a top-GM game saw:} 7... Nd7 8. Nb3 Bb6 9. Ng5 Bxb3 10. axb3 f6
11. Nf3 Nf8 12. Nd2 Qd7 13. Nc4 Ne6 14. Kh1 {Anand,V (2756)-Giri,A (2779)
Amsterdam 2019}) 8. Nb3 a5 $146 {Aronian tries to improve on the play of
Domingues.} ({In his first USA championship he defended the black colour with:} 
8... Qe7 9. Na5 O-O-O 10. Bd2 Bg4 11. Rb1 Nd7 12. Nc4 Qf6 13. b4 Nf8 14. h3
Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Qxf3 16. gxf3 Ne6 {Robson,R (2667) -Dominguez Perez,L (2739)
Saint Louis 2019}) 9. Qe1 {White finds a good idea.} a4 10. Na5 Qb8 ({Worse is:
} 10... Ra7 11. Be3 c5 12. b4 {with unpleasant pin.}) 11. b4 {The point behind
White's idea. Not only the knight is defended, but the bishop will get a
chance to be developed on the long diagonal.} Bg4 ({White is better after:} 
11... axb3 12. axb3 Nd7 13. Bb2 O-O 14. d4) ({However, the immediate:} 11...
O-O {was OK for the second player, as he needs not to worry about the possible
knight jumps, as in the line:} 12. Bb2 Nd7 13. Ng5 Bg4 14. h3 ({Or} 14. f3 Bh5
15. Nc4) 14... Bh5 15. g4 Bg6 {in both cases with a reasonable position for
Black.}) 12. Nh4 O-O 13. Nc4 Be6 {It seems as Aronian has managed to equalize
comfortably, but the next strong move reveals he still has problems:} 14. Nxd6
$1 {[%csl Gc1,Re6] In the opposite-coloured bishop middlegame White can develop
the initiative on the colour of his "extra" bishop.} cxd6 15. f4 exf4 $1 {
The only move.} ({Otherwise White will always have a pleasant choice of taking
on e5 in a good moment or advancing the f-pawn further:} 15... Re8 16. fxe5 (
16. f5 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5,Gh2h3]}) 16... dxe5 17. Nf5 {with advantage for
White.}) 16. Bxf4 Re8 17. a3 ({More accurate was:} 17. Nf3 {The idea is to
meet the freeing d6-d5 advance the proper way. Say:} Nh5 (17... h6 {will be
met with} 18. c4) 18. Be3 d5 19. e5 $1 {Now White does not fear:} Bg4 20. Qf2
Bxf3 21. Qxf3 Qxe5 22. Qxf7+ Kh8 23. Rae1 {with an edge for the first player.})
17... Nh5 18. Bd2 d5 {Otherwise White will quickly build pressure on the
kingside.} 19. Qe2 ({Here too:} 19. e5 {was possible but it promised White far
less than in the line from above after:} f6 20. Bc3 Qa7+ 21. Qf2 Qxf2+ 22. Rxf2
Rad8 23. Bd4 fxe5 24. Bxe5 Rf8 {White is somewhat better, but not as much as
in the middlegame.}) 19... Nf6 ({Missing the firs chance to centralize the
queen:} 19... Qe5 $1 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Ge5f6] and prevent the kingside assault.}
) 20. Rxf6 $1 {[%csl Rf6] Dominguez seizes his chance. On the top-level, these
are sacrifices which people do "by-the-hand", without much thinking. With the
kingside weakened, and the lack of another defender on the dark-squares the
attack runs by itself.} gxf6 21. Rf1 dxe4 $2 {Now it is practically over.} ({
The last chance was the centralization (again!) with:} 21... Qe5 $1 {True, in
this case, Aronian should have found the neat resource:} 22. Qe1 c5 $3 ({But not
} 22... dxe4 23. Bc3 {[%csl Rf6,Rg8][%cal Rc3f6] When White will soon win on
the dark-squares as in the game.}) 23. bxc5 dxe4 {with the idea:} 24. Bc3 Qxc5+
25. Kh1 exd3 {with huge complications.}) 22. Bc3 Qd6 23. Bxf6 {[%csl Gf6,Rg8]
[%cal Ge2h5,Gh5g5,Gg5g8,Gh5h6,Gh6g7,Rf1f3,Rf3g3] The attack is irresistable.
From their comfortable positions the white pieces get closer and closer to the
enemy king with every move.} h6 24. Qh5 Kh7 25. Nf5 Qf8 ({Or} 25... Bxf5 26.
Qxf7#) 26. dxe4 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Gf1,Gf5,Gf6,Gh5][%cal Gf1f3,Gf3g3,Gg3h3,Gf3f4,
Gf4g4,Gg4h4] Dominguez knows that the black king is priority.} ({White could
have won enough material already to win without much ado:} 26. Bg7 Qxg7 27.
Nxg7 Kxg7 28. Qe5+ {but the move in the game is more convincing.}) 26... Rad8
27. Rf4 Rd2 28. Rg4 Rd1+ 29. Kf2 Rd2+ 30. Ke1 Rxc2 31. Bg7 1-0

