{[%evp 0,155,18,31,15,13,13,15,18,-4,15,1,20,7,16,16,4,-10,-5,-11,9,8,15,-12,
-5,-6,1,1,0,5,0,0,-6,-16,-22,-40,-9,-11,-5,17,-1,-1,22,-8,18,41,55,67,84,61,59,
62,57,55,55,55,57,72,68,39,57,91,9,3,89,-11,-15,-12,52,83,125,65,90,142,191,
260,197,244,343,285,282,270,270,273,273,270,268,269,269,269,285,283,284,284,
342,320,339,342,332,342,342,330,330,297,302,281,330,330,338,338,346,347,371,
370,506,565,592,597,616,374,386,420,463,491,566,528,528,420,554,557,566,571,
574,606,647,623,729,762,850,858,870,473,487,385,487,529,755,738,759,776,855,
907,1001,1558,1699,702,881,926]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 (3... Nf6 4. d3
d6 5. O-O Be7 6. c3 O-O 7. Re1 a6 8. Ba4 Re8 9. Nbd2 b5 10. Bc2 Bf8 11. d4 Bb7
12. a4 ({With so many online games going on it was not difficult to find a top
GM recent discussion:} 12. b3 b4 13. Bb2 a5 14. d5 Nb8 15. Nc4 c6 16. dxc6 Nxc6
17. a3 {Nepomniachtchi,I (2784)-Caruana,F (2835) chess24.com INT 2020}) 12...
Nb8 13. Bd3 {The better diagonal for the bishop in this line. White keeps the
road clear for his queenside pawns.} c6 {[#]} 14. b3 $146 {Solid, Ruy Lopez
play by Svidler.} ({The predecessor saw the immediate:} 14. b4 Nbd7 15. Nb3 Qc7
16. dxe5 dxe5 17. Bg5 Re6 18. Na5 Bc8 19. Bd2 Nb6 20. axb5 cxb5 21. Qe2 Re8 22.
c4 {Slobodjan,R (2458)-Kreuzer,M (2335) Kelheim 2017}) 14... Nbd7 15. Qc2 Qc7
16. Bb2 Nh5 (16... g6 {looks more in the spirit of the line.}) 17. Bf1 {
White is not impressed by the knight manoeuvre and hides the bishop from the
annoying knight while keeping the pressure.} Nf4 18. g3 Ne6 19. b4 {The time
for this move came. Now White is ready to manipulate the pawn structure in his
favour with timely c3-c4 or send his knight all the way to the a5 outpost.} Nb6
20. axb5 cxb5 {Carlsen is avoiding the symmetrical pawn structure, but this
turns out to be a mistake.} ({After the correct:} 20... axb5 21. dxe5 dxe5 22.
Rxa8 Rxa8 {White will keep slight initiative with:} 23. c4 {Although the
following trades may exhaust the position to a draw:} Bxb4 24. cxb5 cxb5 25.
Qxc7 Nxc7 26. Bxe5 Ne6 27. Bxb5 Rd8 28. Re2 Nd7 29. Bb2 Ndc5 {and despite the
extra pawn White can hardly make any progress.}) 21. d5 $1 {[%csl Gd5] Svidler
locks the position just in time.} Nd4 {The only active try.} (21... Nd8 22. Nh4
({Or:} 22. c4 {is not what Black plays the Ruy Lopez for!})) 22. Nxd4 exd4 23.
c4 $1 {[%csl Rd4] But now another problem becomes obvious- the d4 pawn is
doomed.} Rac8 ({The immediate attempt for a counterplay:} 23... f5 {May
backfire after:} 24. Bxd4 fxe4 25. Nxe4 Nxd5 26. Ng5 $1 {With winning kingside
attack, one beautiful line running:} Nf6 27. Bd3 h6 28. Bb6 $3 Qxb6 29. Bh7+
Kh8 30. Nf7#) 24. Bxd4 Nxc4 25. Nxc4 bxc4 {The d4 weakness was traded for
another one on c4. The pawn on a6 is in trouble too. All in all, Black is in
huge trouble but both players are under thirty seconds on the clock.} 26. Rac1
{Played instantly.} ({While observing the game online I thought Svidler would
choose:} 26. Bc3 {[%cal Gc2d2,Gd2d4,Gg3g4,Gh2h4,Gh4h5,Gg4g5,Gf2f4,Gf4f5] and
would win by transferring his queen to d4 with direct kingside attack.}) ({
Also good was:} 26. Bh3 $5 {depriving Black of any active chances.}) 26... f5
$1 {Now Carlsen finds a way to muddy the waters.} 27. Bh3 fxe4 28. Bxc8 Rxc8
29. Qxe4 Qf7 30. Qg4 (30. Qe6 Bxd5) 30... Qxd5 {With the drop of this key pawn
White's advantage is lessened severely. The two bishops and the potential
central passers keep Black in the game.} 31. Qe6+ Qxe6 32. Rxe6 Kf7 33. Re3 Bd5
34. Bc3 Bc6 35. Ra1 Ra8 (35... Bb5 $5 {keeping the rook on the c-file might
have been somewhat better.}) 36. Rae1 ({It made sense to expand on the
kingside at once:} 36. h4 $5) 36... d5 ({Here better was:} 36... Rd8 37. Ra1
Bb5 38. Rd1 d5 {with full compensation for the exchange. More importantly-
Black would have kept the enemy pieces away.}) 37. Rf3+ Kg8 38. Re6 {Now
Svidler seizes the initiative once again.} Rc8 39. Rf4 Bb5 ({Missing the
chance to activate his second bishop with:} 39... g6 $1 40. Kf1 Bb5 {When a
draw is the most likely result after:} 41. Ke2 d4 42. Rxd4 Bg7 43. Kd2) 40. h4
Rd8 ({Here:} 40... g6 {looked less logical but was still the thing to do:} 41.
h5 Bh6 $1 42. Rf3 Bg7 $1 {This would lift the blockade of the black passers
and White would be forced to go for perpetual sooner or later, say in the line:
} 43. Bxg7 Kxg7 44. Re7+ Kh6 45. hxg6 Kxg6 46. Re6+) 41. Rb6 Bd6 42. Rg4 Rd7 ({
It is too late for:} 42... Bf8 43. Rb7) 43. h5 ({Svidler misses a tactical
shot:} 43. Bxg7 $1 {when Black's position would fall apart after:} Rxg7 44.
Rxg7+ Kxg7 45. Rxd6 d4 46. Rxd4) 43... h6 ({The last chance was:} 43... Bc7 44.
Re6 Bd8) 44. Rg6 (44. Bxg7 $1 {was still there.}) 44... Bf8 45. Bd4 Bxb4 ({
After:} 45... Rc7 $1 {anything was still possible as the black passers are set
to run:} 46. Bc3 $2 d4 $1) 46. Rb8+ Kh7 47. f4 $3 {Without any thought Svidler
produces mate a-la Carlsen.} c3 48. Rxh6+ $3 {Copycat by the world champion's
final touch of his match against Karjakin. 1-0 (48) Svidler,P (2754)-Carlsen,M
(2887) FIDE Online Steinitz Memorial 2020 [Bojkov,Dejan]}) 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O
Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. a4 b4 9. a5 d6 10. d3 Be6 11. Bxe6 fxe6 12. Nbd2
Rb8 {This line was heavily discussed last year in Saint Louis.} 13. Nb3 ({
Carlsen chose instead:} 13. c3 Qe8 14. Nc4 Qg6 15. h3 Nd7 16. Be3 d5 17. Ncd2
bxc3 18. bxc3 Nc5 19. Bxc5 Bxc5 20. Qa4 {and went on to win later, Carlsen, M 
(2822)-Aronian, L (2809) Saint Louis 2017. However, there remained a lot of
questions about White's chances in this game.}) 13... Qc8 {[#]} 14. h3 $146 {
So improves on another Saint Louis game.} ({In that one the world champion
defended the black colour after} 14. Qe2 Nd8 15. d4 exd4 16. Nbxd4 c5 17. Nb3 e5
18. Nbd2 Ne6 {Caruana,F (2807) -Carlsen,M (2822) Saint Louis 2017}) 14... Nd8
15. Be3 c5 16. Nbd2 Nc6 17. c3 Rb5 18. d4 ({White can, of course, keep the pawn
with either} 18. Nc4) ({Or} 18. Nb3 {but Black would have no problems at all
in these lines.}) 18... exd4 {An ambitious move.} ({Aronian saw that he can
equalize with:} 18... bxc3 19. bxc3 exd4 20. cxd4 c4 ({Probably also good is} 
20... cxd4 21. Nxd4 Nxd4 22. Bxd4 Nd7) ({Maybe even} 20... Nxa5 21. dxc5 dxc5
22. Qa4 {is a better version of the game continuation for Black. Although with
so many weaknesses White still has decent compensation for a pawn.}) 21. Nxc4
Nxe4 {"should be around equal" (Aronian)}) (18... Nxa5 $2 {should be avoided
though as it drops a piece after} 19. dxe5 dxe5 (19... bxc3 20. bxc3 dxe5 21.
c4) 20. c4) 19. cxd4 Nxa5 20. dxc5 dxc5 {[%csl Ra5,Ra6,Rc4,Re6] In return for
the pawn White has active pieces and can exploit the many weaknesses in the
opponent's camp.} 21. Ra2 {"I kind of prepared this line" (So). He later
revealed that he considered the position equal.} Qb7 ({Here and on the next
moves Aronian avoids} 21... Nc6 {in order to keep the c4 square under control
and not to let the white queen there.}) ({The American GM expected} 21... Nd7 {
[%csl Gc6][%cal Gd7b8,Gb8c6] with the idea Nd7-b8-c6.}) 22. b3 ({If} 22. Qa1
Bd8) 22... Kh8 {"I was a little surprised by this, but it is probably a good
move." (So)} ({Aronian disliked the position after:} 22... Nxe4 23. Nxe4 Qxe4
24. Bg5 Qb7 25. Qe2 Bxg5 26. Nxg5 {"maybe it holds somehow but it was not the
position I wanted to get" (Aronian)} Qd5 27. Nxe6 {[%csl Ge6]}) ({Black also
disliked} 22... Nd7 23. Qe2 {as he felt he should keep the knight on f6.}) 23.
Qc2 {So is combining threats against the weaknesses on the queenside with
threats on the opposite wing. Now e4-e5 followed by Nf3-g5 is always a threat.}
Nd7 ({If} 23... Nc6 {to centralize this knight, then either} 24. Nc4 ({Or} 24.
Ng5)) 24. Rea1 Bd8 25. Nc4 {[%csl Gc4]} ({Aronian saw the excellent reply to} 
25. e5 c4 26. Nxc4 Nxc4 27. Qxc4 Rxf3 $1 {with fantastic counter-attack.})
25... Nxc4 26. Qxc4 {[%csl Gc4,Re6][%cal Rc4g8]} Bf6 ({After} 26... a5 27. Rd1
$1 {is strong.} ({Rather than} 27. Qxe6 Rb6 28. Qc4 Rd6 {although here too,
White is better.})) 27. Rd1 Qc6 28. Rad2 {[%csl Gc4,Gd1,Gd2][%cal Gd1d8]
Little by little the white pieces occupied commanding positions.} Nb6 (28...
Ne5 {is unpleasant for Black after} 29. Nxe5 Bxe5 30. Rd8 {(Aronian, So)}) 29.
Qc2 Qc7 {After this move Black's position becomes too loose.} ({Black rejected
} 29... Qc8 $1 {on the account of} 30. e5 Bd8 31. Bg5 {But this seems way
better than the game continuation after} (31. Bxc5 $2 Rxc5 32. Rxd8 Rxc2 {
wins for Black.}) 31... Nd5 $1 {This was probably Black's best chance.}) ({
After} 29... e5 30. Bg5 $1 {is strong for White (Aronian)}) 30. e5 $1 {Breaks
open the position fr his active pieces. The rook on b5 and the knight are out
of the game and So attacks practically with an extra rook.} ({Also quite
unpleasant for the second player was the resource} 30. Bg5 $5 {(Aronian) with
the threat e4-e5 and if} c4 31. Bxf6 gxf6 32. Nd4 Re5 33. f4 {wins material
for White.}) 30... Be7 (30... Bxe5 $2 {drops material heavily after} 31. Ng5 g6
32. Nxe6) ({Here} 30... Bd8 {does not work (see the line from the previous
comment) due to} 31. Bxc5 $1 Rxc5 32. Rxd8 Rxc2 33. Rxf8#) 31. Nd4 Rc8 ({
Perhaps the last chance was the eventual endgame after} 31... Qxe5 32. Nxb5
axb5 33. Re2 Qc3) 32. Nxe6 $1 {White keeps playing for the attack.} ({"It does
not make any sense to take the exchange"} 32. Nxb5 axb5 33. f4 Nd5 {"as Black
is at least equal" (Aronian, So). The black connected passers are perfectly
supported by all his pieces.}) 32... Qxe5 33. Nf4 {Aronian did not expect this
and "relaxed too soon" after seeing it. He later called the move "excellent
practical chance."} ({Aronian spend almost all his remaining time on the sharp
and beautiful lines:} 33. Rd6 $1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ge3f4] with the threat
Be3-f4! (So did not see this) If} Kg8 ({The main tactical point of the move is
that} 33... Bxd6 $1 34. Ng5 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Rg5f7,Rc2h7] is a nasty double
attack.}) ({Probably} 33... Re8 {leaves defensive chances to Black.}) 34. Bf4
Qf6 35. Ng5 {wins for White.}) ({Black was also afraid of} 33. Nd8 {when after}
Kg8 34. Rd7 c4 ({Aronian intended} 34... Qf6 {but this loses to} 35. Bg5 $3
Qxg5 36. Qe2 $1) (34... h6) 35. Bd4 Qf5 $2 ({However} 35... Nxd7 $1 36. Bxe5
Nxe5 {provides Black drawing chances.}) 36. Rxe7 Rxd8 (36... Qxc2 37. Re8#) 37.
Rxg7+ {and White should win.}) 33... Rf8 {"is bad" (So); "is a terrible move" 
(Aronian)} (33... Kg8 $1 {was mandatory} 34. Re2 Bf8 {when Black can cement
his position.}) 34. Re2 $1 {Now the black pieces are once again loose.} Qc3 ({
Last chance was} 34... Bf6 $5) ({Aronian's initial plan was} 34... Qf5 35. Qxf5
Rxf5 {but then he spotted} 36. Bc1 $1 {"and Black can resign"(Aronian). For
example} Bf8 37. Rd8 Kg8 38. Ree8 c4 39. g4 Rf6 40. Ne6) 35. Qb1 $1 {[%csl Gb1]
} (35. Qa2 {with the same idea was also very strong as indicated by the
Armenian GM.}) 35... Qf6 ({Or} 35... Nc8 36. Bd2 Qf6 37. Ne6 Rg8 38. Bg5 Qf7
39. Bxe7 Nxe7 (39... Qxe7 40. Nd4) 40. Ng5 Qg6 41. Qxg6 Nxg6 42. Nf7#) 36. Bc1
$3 {[%cal Gc1b2] "Here the game is already finished. It is just (white) pieces
coming." (Aronian)} c4 ({A curious line is} 36... Qf7 37. Bb2 Bf6 38. Bxf6 Qxf6
39. Ne6 Rg8 40. Nc7 Ra5 41. Ne8 Qg5 42. Nd6) 37. bxc4 Nxc4 ({Alas,} 37... Rg5 {
does not work due to} 38. Re6 $1 {(Aronian)} ({But not} 38. Ne6 $2 Rxg2+ $1 39.
Kxg2 Qf3+)) 38. Re6 Qg5 {Sacrifices the queen in the vain hope of a fortress.}
({Or else Black will lose material on the pin} 38... Qf7 39. Rd7 Re8 40. Qe4)
39. Ng6+ ({There was an alternative win} 39. Rd7 Bf6 40. Rf7 $1 Rbb8 (40... Rg8
41. Rexf6) 41. Rxf8+ Rxf8 42. Qxb4 Rc8 43. Qxc4 $1) 39... Qxg6 40. Rxg6 hxg6
41. Qe4 {This is the problem. More material is lost.} Bf6 42. Qxc4 b3 43. Ba3
Rfb8 ({If} 43... b2 44. Bxf8 b1=Q 45. Rxb1 Rxb1+ 46. Kh2) 44. Rb1 b2 45. h4 {
The rest is a good technique by So.} (45. Qa4 $5 a5 46. h4) 45... Ra5 (45... a5
46. Bd6 R8b7 47. g4 Rb3 48. Kg2 {(Aronian, So)}) 46. Qd3 Rd8 (46... Bxh4 47.
Rxb2) 47. Qb3 Rc8 48. Qb7 Rd8 49. Qb3 Rc8 50. Qb4 Rb5 51. Qg4 Rc3 (51... Rcb8
52. Qxg6) 52. Bxb2 Rxb2 53. Rxb2 Rc1+ 54. Kh2 Bxb2 55. Qxg6 Ra1 56. g4 a5 57.
Qh5+ Kg8 58. Qb5 Ba3 ({The utility of the kingside pawns is revealed after} 
58... Bf6 59. Qe8+ Kh7 60. g5 Bc3 (60... Bb2 61. Qe4+ Kg8 62. g6 Kf8 63. Qe6)
61. Qh5+ Kg8 62. g6 Kf8 63. Qc5+) 59. Qe5 Rd1 60. Qe6+ Kh7 61. Qe4+ Kh8 62.
Qa8+ Kh7 63. Qxa5 Bd6+ 64. Kg2 Rd4 65. Qf5+ Kh8 66. Qh5+ Kg8 67. g5 Kf8 68. Qg6
Be7 69. Qf5+ Ke8 70. Kh3 Rd6 71. Qh7 Kf7 72. f4 Rd4 73. Qf5+ Ke8 74. Qe5 Rb4
75. Kg4 Kf8 76. Qf5+ Ke8 77. Qe6 Rd4 (77... Kf8 78. Qc8+ Kf7 79. g6+ Kxg6 80.
Qf5+ Kh6 81. Qh5#) 78. Qe5 1-0

