initiative with:} 23. c4 {Although the following trades may exhaust the
position to a draw:} Bxb4 24. cxb5 cxb5 25. Qxc7 Nxc7 26. Bxe5 Ne6 27. Bxb5 Rd8
28. Re2 Nd7 29. Bb2 Ndc5 {and despite the extra pawn White can hardly make any
progress.}) 21. d5 $1 {Svidler locks the position just in time.} Nd4 {The only
active try.} (21... Nd8 22. Nh4 ({Or:} 22. c4 {is not what Black plays the Ruy
Lopez for!})) 22. Nxd4 exd4 23. c4 $1 {But now another problem becomes
obvious- the d4 pawn is doomed.} Rac8 ({The immediate attempt for a
counterplay:} 23... f5 {May backfire after:} 24. Bxd4 fxe4 25. Nxe4 Nxd5 26.
Ng5 $1 {With winning kingside attack, one beautiful line running:} Nf6 27. Bd3
h6 28. Bb6 $3 Qxb6 29. Bh7+ Kh8 30. Nf7#) 24. Bxd4 Nxc4 25. Nxc4 bxc4 {The d4
weakness was traded for another one on c4. The pawn on a6 is in trouble too.
All in all, Black is in huge trouble but both players are under thirty seconds
on the clock.} 26. Rac1 {Played instantly.} ({While observing the game online
I thought Svidler would choose:} 26. Bc3 {and would win by transferring his
queen to d4 with a direct kingside attack.}) ({Also good was:} 26. Bh3 $5 {
depriving Black of any active chances.}) 26... f5 $1 {Now Carlsen finds a way
to muddy the waters.} 27. Bh3 fxe4 28. Bxc8 Rxc8 29. Qxe4 Qf7 30. Qg4 (30. Qe6
Bxd5) 30... Qxd5 {With the drop of this key pawn White's advantage is lessened
severely. The two bishops and the potential central passers keep Black in the
game.} 31. Qe6+ Qxe6 32. Rxe6 Kf7 33. Re3 Bd5 34. Bc3 Bc6 35. Ra1 Ra8 (35...
Bb5 $5 {keeping the rook on the c-file might have been somewhat better.}) 36.
Rae1 ({It made sense to expand on the kingside at once:} 36. h4 $5) 36... d5 ({
Here better was:} 36... Rd8 37. Ra1 Bb5 38. Rd1 d5 {with full compensation for
the exchange. More importantly- Black would have kept the enemy pieces away.})
37. Rf3+ Kg8 38. Re6 {Now Svidler seizes the initiative once again.} Rc8 39.
Rf4 Bb5 ({Missing the chance to activate his second bishop with:} 39... g6 $1
40. Kf1 Bb5 {When a draw is the most likely result after:} 41. Ke2 d4 42. Rxd4
Bg7 43. Kd2) 40. h4 Rd8 ({Here:} 40... g6 {looked less logical but was still
the thing to do:} 41. h5 Bh6 $1 42. Rf3 Bg7 $1 {This would lift the blockade
of the black passers and White would be forced to go for perpetual sooner or
later, say in the line:} 43. Bxg7 Kxg7 44. Re7+ Kh6 45. hxg6 Kxg6 46. Re6+) 41.
Rb6 Bd6 42. Rg4 Rd7 ({It is too late for:} 42... Bf8 43. Rb7) 43. h5 ({Svidler
misses a tactical shot:} 43. Bxg7 $1 {when Black's position would fall apart
after:} Rxg7 44. Rxg7+ Kxg7 45. Rxd6 d4 46. Rxd4) 43... h6 ({The last chance
was:} 43... Bc7 44. Re6 Bd8) 44. Rg6 (44. Bxg7 $1 {was still there.}) 44... Bf8
45. Bd4 Bxb4 ({After:} 45... Rc7 $1 {anything was still possible as the black
passers are set to run:} 46. Bc3 $2 d4 $1) 46. Rb8+ Kh7 47. f4 $3 {Without any
thought Svidler produces mate a-la Carlsen.} c3 48. Rxh6+ $3 {Copycat by the
world champion's final touch of his match against Karjakin.} 1-0

