{[%evp 0,77,19,31,34,42,8,17,36,14,23,-12,-2,1,-11,-13,35,-15,-12,-11,3,-15,-1,
-57,-5,-55,-40,-38,-47,-15,-10,-3,-5,0,-16,-25,-19,-12,0,6,17,32,39,19,6,18,20,
20,54,45,65,75,59,55,74,23,41,42,51,3,35,13,33,0,-11,0,64,71,70,87,114,260,258,
305,281,302,302,283,365,365]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 (3... a6 4. Ba4
Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 {The world champion had tested the Open Ruy Lopez three times
in 2015.} 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5 Be6 9. Be3 {And a micro-surprise in
return. In seven out of the eight games that Hou had played against this
pasrticular line she opted for the main lines after 9. Nb1-d2. In just one she
tried 9.Bc1-e3 but it was against none else but Viktor Kortschnoj!} Be7 {
The main line. The above-mentioned game continued:} (9... Bc5 {This move is
considered dubous as White is usually happy to trade the dark-squared bishops.
However after} 10. Bxc5 Nxc5 11. Nd4 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Nb7 13. c3 c5 14. Qf4 Na5
15. Bc2 h6 $1 16. Nd2 Qg5 17. Qxg5 hxg5 {Black successfully solved his opening
problems and went on to win later, Hou, Y (2523) -Kortschnoj, V (2610) Paks 2007}
) 10. c3 O-O 11. Nbd2 Qd7 12. Bc2 Nxd2 (12... f5 {is more common.}) 13. Qxd2
Bg4 14. Bf4 {Hou allows the doubling of her pawns but keeps a strong grip in
the centre. According to my Megabase, this is an over-the-board novelty.} ({
Another way to play it is} 14. Qd3 g6 15. Bh6 {although Black did great after}
Rfe8 16. Rfe1 Bf5 17. Qd2 Bxc2 18. Qxc2 Nd8 19. Rad1 Ne6 {with an excellent
position for the second player in Kokarev, D (2638) -Short, N (2664) Kolkata 2015
}) 14... Bxf3 15. gxf3 Rad8 $146 {Only this move is an actual novelty. One
correspondence game saw:} (15... Nd8 16. Rad1 c6 17. Kh1 f5 18. Rg1 Ne6 {
and with this excellent blockading piece on e6 Black can hardly be worse,
Nyman,S-Lilloni,L Italy 1972}) 16. Rfd1 Qe6 {The slightly weird} (16... Bh4 {
deserved attention, trying to prevent the set-up with Bf4-g3 and the pawn
advance to f5.}) 17. Qe3 {"I started to dislike my position" Muzychuk. Hou
Yifan considered it "very complicated."} Rd7 {This move seems as the beginning
of Black's actual problems.} ({Muzychuk did not like} 17... Na5 {due to} 18. b3
c5 19. a4 Nc6 20. axb5 axb5 21. Ra6 {and White is more pleasant. One key point
here is that} Ra8 {is strongly met with} 22. Qd3 $1) ({However} 17... Bh4 $5 {
was still very interesting.}) ({Another interesting idea was} 17... g6 18. Bg3
{and only now} Na5 19. b3 c5 20. a4 Nc6 21. axb5 axb5 22. Ra6 Ra8 {In
comparison to the above-mentioned line there is no Qe3-d3 killer here.}) 18.
Bg3 {With the obvious intention f3-f4-f5.} g6 {[#]} ({On} 18... Na5 {White is
not obliged to go for a slightly better endgame with} 19. f4 ({But can play
for more instead} 19. b3 c5 20. a4 {with advantage for White.}) 19... f5 20.
exf6 (20. b3 c5) 20... Qxe3 21. fxe3 Bxf6 $14) ({The problem with the immediate
} 18... f5 19. exf6 Qxf6 20. Bb3 {is that the d5 pawn is in danger.}) 19. a4 $1
{[%cal Ga1a8] Strong play by Hou. The open "a" file will help her kingside
attack.} Nd8 ({Muzychuk did not like} 19... b4 20. f4 ({Or the immediate} 20.
a5 bxc3 21. bxc3 {followed by Bc2-a4 "and nobody knows what is my rook doing
on d7" Muzychuk.}) 20... f5 21. a5) 20. axb5 axb5 21. f4 f6 (21... f5 22. exf6
{will most likely transpose.}) ({he pawn cannot be allowed on f5-} 21... c6 22.
f5 gxf5 23. Qf3 {[%csl Rf5,Rg8][%cal Rc2f5] as the light-squares in Black's
camp will crumble.}) 22. exf6 {Bojkov, Dejan: 'will most likely transpose.'}
Qxf6 {Here an endgame will be impossible since after} (22... Qxe3 23. fxe3 Bxf6
24. Bb3 c6 25. e4 {White would win a pawn.}) 23. Qe2 {There is no need to
sacrifice anything:} (23. f5 gxf5 24. Be5 Qe6 25. Kh1 Bf6 {although this looks
very attractive for White as well.}) 23... c6 24. Qg4 Rb7 25. f5 {[%csl Gf5]
White achieved big advantage and on the top of that, the world champion was in
serious time trouble.} Bd6 $1 {The best defense is the counter-attack.} (25...
Kg7 {does not save the pawn due to} 26. fxg6 hxg6 27. Be5 $1 Qxe5 28. Qxg6+ Kh8
29. Qh7#) 26. Ra6 $1 {This is what the "a" file was opened for. Worse was} (26.
fxg6 Bxg3 27. Qxg3 hxg6 {when the pawn is invincible} 28. Bxg6 $2 (28. Qxg6+ $2
Rg7) 28... Rg7) 26... Rg7 27. fxg6 Bc5 {The most stubborn defense was} (27...
Bxg3 28. Qxg3 Qe7 ({But not} 28... hxg6 $2 29. Rxd5 $1) 29. Bd3 hxg6 {wehn
White is clearly better but there will be a lot of fight ahead.}) 28. Kg2 $1 {
[%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5] Moves out of the pin and prepares the advance of the "f"
pawn.} (28. Kh1 $1 {was also strong. As long as the king moves away from the
check White is doing great.}) 28... hxg6 {In order to avoid the loss of the
pawn in the line} (28... Qe7 29. f4 hxg6 30. Bxg6) 29. Rxd5 Bxf2 ({White wins
a lot of pawns in the line} 29... cxd5 30. Rxf6 Rxf6 31. Qg5 Be7 32. Qxd5+) 30.
Bb3 $1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gb3g8] A pretty ambush. The threat of discovered check
forces} Ne6 ({As} 30... Nf7 {allows} 31. Bxf2) 31. Rd6 {But now the knight is
under a deadly pin.} Bc5 {The last little trick in the time trouble.} 32. Qxe6+
{1-0 (32) Hou Yifan (2673)-Muzychuk,M (2554) Lviv UKR 2016 [Bojkov, Dejan]} (
32. Rxe6 $4 {would be slightly embarrassing} Qf1#)) 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O
d6 7. Ba4 Ne7 ({Carlsen also faced:} 7... Bb6 8. Nbd2 Ne7 9. Nc4 Ng6 10. h3 h6
11. Bc2 Be6 12. Nxb6 axb6 13. d4 {as in Carlsen,M (2835)-Andreikin,D (2719) St
Petersburg 2018}) 8. Bc2 $146 {White prepares d3-d4 but does not yet show
where will his queenside knight go.} ({It is curious that the world champion
tries to improve on another game played in Russia:} 8. Nbd2 Ng6 9. d4 Bb6 10.
Bc2 Re8 11. Re1 c6 12. h3 h6 13. a4 Be6 14. Nf1 {1-0 (22) Karjakin,S (2753)
-Jakovenko, D (2735) St Petersburg 2018}) 8... Ng6 9. d4 Bb6 10. a4 c6 11. dxe5
({White can always try to switch to the above-mentioned game with} 11. Nbd2 {
but apparently, he was not happy with the arising positions.}) 11... Nxe5 12.
Nxe5 dxe5 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. a5 Bc5 15. Nd2 ({"When I went for this position I
intended to go:"} 15. b4 {"but it is not very good." (Carlsen)} Be7 16. f3 Be6
17. Na3 (17. Be3 c5 $1 {(Grischuk)}) 17... b5 $1 {with good game for Black.})
15... Be6 {The opening went fine for Grischuk and he enjoys comfortable
equality. Black's problem was purely psychological. As Grischuk put it he
clearly understood that this same position can be achieved with reversed
colours. Obviously, he became extra confident and committed a serious inaccuracy.
} 16. Re1 b5 {"Very big mistake." (Grischuk)} 17. Nb3 Bxb3 {The Russian GM did
not like neither of the alternatives, but it seems as this is the real mistake.
} ({If} 17... Bd6 18. Bg5 {"and I achieve nothing" (Grischuk) was however his
best option. After:} h6 19. Bxf6 gxf6 20. Rad1 Be7 {Black should not
experience problems.}) ({If} 17... Be7 18. a6 {"then Nb3-a5 was very strong" 
(Grischuk) Even that should not be as horrible after:} Rd7 19. Na5 Bc5 20. h3 (
{Or} 20. Nxc6 Ng4 21. Rf1 Bc4) 20... Rc8 {with normal play for Black.}) 18.
Bxb3 {[%csl Gb3,Gc1]} Ng4 19. Re2 {Now White is clearly better thanks to his
bishop pair. Carlsen quickly builds upon his advantage.} Rd6 20. Bg5 $1 {
[%csl Rc5,Rd6][%cal Rg5e7,Re7c5] Wins an important tempo to bring the
queenside rook out.} Kf8 (20... h6 21. Be7 {loses on the spot.}) 21. Rf1 Nf6
22. g3 {[%csl Rd1,Rd2][%cal Gf2f4,Rd8d1,Rb3d1,Rg5d2] In order to prepare f2-f4
which will open both files and diagonals for his pieces. Notice that Black
holds the d-file but it is completely useless for his as the bishops control
all the squares. In the meanwhile, Carlsen wants to open a file for his own
rooks.} a6 23. Kg2 Nd7 24. Bc1 Ba7 25. f4 f6 ({Anytime the f-file is open:} 
25... exf4 {it is soon over:} 26. Bxf4 Rf6 ({Or} 26... Rg6 27. Rd2) 27. e5 Rg6
28. e6 {[%csl Rf7,Rf8][%cal Gf4b8,Gb3g8]}) 26. h4 Re8 ({Carlsen thought} 26...
h5 {might be a defence, although then White can switch to play on the d-file
with:} 27. Ree1 Ke7 28. Rd1 Rxd1 29. Rxd1 {[%csl Gb3,Gc1][%cal Gd1d8]}) 27. h5
{[%cal Rh5h6]} h6 {Forced.} ({Or else White will make it to the f6 pawn after
say:} 27... Re7 28. h6 {[%csl Re5,Rf6,Rg7]} g6 29. fxe5 Nxe5 30. Bg5 Nd7 31. e5
{[%csl Rf6]}) 28. Ba2 $1 {[%csl Ga2][%cal Gd7c5,Gc5b3] One of those little
moves that make a big difference at the end. The bishop steps away from the
possible tempos after Nd7-c5 and eventually d3.} c5 {"Ugly as it blocks the
bishop" (Carlsen)} ({The knight cannot move:} 28... Nc5 29. fxe5 Rxe5 30. Bf4 {
[%csl Rd6,Re5]}) ({But perhaps Black should have tried:} 28... exf4 29. gxf4
Nc5 {with the idea:} 30. e5 Nd3 $1) 29. Be3 $1 {Grischuk praised Carlsen's
play after the game and especially this decision. It was not very obvious what
the pins and the counterpins will lead to, plus White sacrifices a pawn. But
the world champion had it all right.} exf4 30. gxf4 (30. Bxf4 Ne5 {[%csl Ge5]
was definitely not the idea.}) 30... Rxe4 31. Bb1 Re7 ({If the rook retreats
on another square like:} 31... Re8 {then Wihte seizes the e-file with decisive
effect:} 32. Rfe1 Rc8 33. Bf2 {[%csl Rf8][%cal Rb1g6,Re2e8,Re8f8] followed by
Bb1-g6 and mate is coming.}) 32. Rfe1 f5 {Missing his chance.} ({Black could
have held the line with the unusual:} 32... Nb8 $1 33. Bf2 Nc6 {intending:} 34.
Bg6 ({Or} 34. Kf3 Rdd7 {In this line White is still much better after:} 35. Bf5
Rxe2 36. Rxe2 Re7 37. Rd2 $1 {but Black can still fight on.}) 34... Rxe2 35.
Rxe2 Ne7) 33. Bxf5 Nf6 {The knight covers the e8 spot, however, Black's ship is
already leaking from far too many holes.} 34. Kf3 Nd5 35. Rd2 $1 {[%csl Rd6]
[%cal Rd2d6] "This was a surprise for me" (Grischuk)} ({Instead he expected:} 
35. Bd2 Rxe2 36. Rxe2 Ne7 {"and it is nothing special" (Grischuk)}) 35... Rd8 (
35... Rxe3+ {loses material after:} 36. Rxe3 Nxe3 37. Rxd6 Nxf5 38. Rxa6 Bb8
39. Ra8) ({Black is also lost after:} 35... Nxe3 36. Rxd6 Nxf5 37. Rxe7 Kxe7 ({
Or} 37... Nxe7 38. Rxa6 Bb8 39. Ra8 Nc6 40. a6 {with the inevitable Ra8xb8.})
38. Rxa6 Bb8 39. Rb6) 36. Be4 {The pins worked in White's favour.} Red7 37. Red1
Nf6 38. Rxd7 Nxd7 39. Rd6 {Black's position collapses, Grischuk saluted the
deserved winner of the Shamkir 2019 Gashimov Memorial.} 1-0

