end of the game.} g6 16. Bb3 Rb8 17. a4 b4 18. Bd5 Ne7 19. Bc4 Rf8 20. Nd5 Nxd5
21. Bxd5 Bg7 (21... Bg4 $142 22. h3 (22. a5 $143 Bg5 23. h3 $140 Bxf3 24. Qxf3
Bd2) 22... Bxf3 23. Qxf3 $14) 22. Nd2 Kh7 (22... a5 $142) 23. a5 Be6 24. Bxe6
fxe6 25. Nc4 $16 {Although the engine at first evaluated that this position is
in favour of Black (!) I am inclined to think that White is strategically
winning. My plan is simple-to put the knight on b6, after which he has or to
stay at one place when I exchange on b4 and later win this pawn, or exchange
on c3, after which I double the rooks on the b file under the knight
protection and penetrate with them in the proper moment.} Rb5 $6 (25... Rf7
26. Nb6 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Rc3b4,Rc5b4,Ra1a4,Ra4b4]} bxc3 27. bxc3 Qh4 28. Qe2 h5
29. Rab1 Rbf8 (29... Rfb7 30. Rb3 (30. Rb2 Bh6 31. Reb1) 30... g5) 30. Rf1) 26.
Qe2 Bf6 27. Reb1 Rb7 28. Nb6 bxc3 29. bxc3 Rbf7 30. Rf1 Bh4 31. g3 Bg5 32. Nc4
Qd7 (32... Rb7 33. Rab1) 33. Rab1 Bd8 34. Rb8 h5 $138 35. Kg2 $6 {I started to
feel quite nervous in his own time trouble, and missed the clear win:} (35.
Rfb1 $142 $1 Rxf2 36. Qxf2 Rxf2 37. Kxf2 Kh6 38. R1b7 Bc7 39. Rh8+ Kg7 (39...
Kg5 40. h4+ Kg4 41. Kg2) 40. Ra8 Kf6 41. h4 $18 {For some reason I thought
that somewhere in these lines he can come with his queen on a4 and find some
perpetual.}) 35... Bc7 36. Rxf8 Rxf8 37. Rb1 Rb8 38. Rxb8 Bxb8 39. Qb2 Qb5 (
39... Ba7 $142 40. h4 $16) 40. Qxb5 axb5 41. Na3 b4 42. Nb5 {Now it is under
control again, though Fritz evaluates for quite a long time that it is
slightly better for Black (!).} Kg7 (42... d5 43. Kf3 b3 44. Ke2 b2 45. Na3 c4
46. dxc4 Bd6 47. Nb1 dxe4 48. Ke3 $18) 43. a6 b3 44. Kf3 Kf6 (44... b2 45. Na3
Ba7 (45... c4 {only chance} 46. dxc4 Ba7 47. Ke2 Bc5 48. Nb1 Kf7 49. Kd3 Bxf2
50. Na3 Ke7 51. Kc2 Kd7 52. Nb5 Kc6 53. a7 Kb7 54. Nxd6+ Kxa7 $16) 46. c4 $18)
45. Ke2 b2 46. Na3 Ke7 (46... d5 47. c4) 47. Kd2 Kd7 48. Kc2 Kc6 49. Nc4 d5 50.
a7 Bxa7 51. Nxe5+ Kd6 52. Nxg6 dxe4 53. dxe4 c4 54. f3 e5 55. Nh4 Ke6 56. Nf5
Bg1 57. h4 {1-0 (57) Bojkov,D (2474)-Van den Doel,E (2581) Zwolle 2007 [Bojkov,
Dejan]}) 3... Nf6 (3... a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. a4 Bd7
9. c3 Na5 10. Ba2 c5 11. Bg5 O-O 12. Nbd2 Rb8 13. axb5 axb5 14. Re1 b4 15. Nc4
Nxc4 16. Bxc4 bxc3 17. bxc3 Qc7 18. Qc2 Bb5 19. Bxb5 Rxb5 {[#]} 20. Bxf6 Bxf6
21. Nd2 {[%csl Gd2,Rf6] In a one-flank play the blocked bishop proves
defenceless against the tricky knight.} Qc6 22. Qa4 Rfb8 23. Nc4 Be7 24. g3 $1
{[%csl Gg3][%cal Gg1g2,Gh2h4] Not only opening air but intending to expand on
the kingside.} Qc8 25. Qd1 g6 26. Kg2 Bf8 27. Qf3 Rb3 28. Rec1 Qe6 29. Ra7 R8b7
30. Rxb7 Rxb7 31. Ra1 {[%csl Ra7,Ra8][%cal Ra8h8,Ra7h7] After the trade of a
rook pair Black can no loger defend both the back ranks.} h5 ({There's no time
to pick up the pawn:} 31... Rb3 32. Ne3 Rxc3 33. Nd5 Rb3 34. Ra8 {[%csl Re8]
[%cal Ra8e8,Rd5f6]} f5 35. g4 $1) 32. Ra8 Kg7 33. Ne3 Rc7 34. Nd5 Rc8 35. Ra7
$1 {[%cal Ga7h7]} Rb8 36. h3 Rd8 37. g4 $1 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Rg4g5,Rd5f6] The
beginning of the decisive attack.} hxg4 38. hxg4 Rd7 39. Ra8 {[%cal Rg4g5,
Rd5f6]} f6 40. g5 f5 41. Qh3 Rf7 42. Re8 $1 {[%csl Re8]} Qxe8 43. Qh6+ Kg8 44.
Qxg6+ Kh8 45. Nf6 {[%cal Rg6g8] 1-0 (45) Carlsen,M (2863)-Tari,A (2633)
Stavanger 2020}) 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O Qe7 7. Nbd2 Bg4 8. h3 Bh5 9. Nc4
Nd7 10. a3 {[#] The world champion is closely watching the efforts of his
competitors and comes up with an improvement upon a very fresh game.} a6 $146 {
A novelty. Carlsen secures the a7-g1 diagonal for his bishop.} ({Unlike the
predecessor:} 10... f6 {Which gave So a chance to bother Black's dark-squared
bishop after:} 11. b4 $1 Bd6 12. Ne3 Nf8 13. c4 Qd7 14. c5 Be7 15. Nxe5 Bxd1
16. Nxd7 Be2 17. Re1 Bxd3 18. Nxf8 Rxf8 19. Nf5 {with pleasant edge for White
in So,W (2767)-Nakamura,H (2745) chess.com INT 2020}) 11. b4 Ba7 12. Be3 {
The black bishop is too strong to be left alive. Plus White is depriving the
opponent of his bishop pair.} Bxe3 13. Nxe3 {The knight moves towards the
optimal square.} ({The opening of the f-file does not seem great due to:} 13.
fxe3 c5) 13... f6 14. Nf5 Qf8 {Carlsen wants to keep his second bishop on
board.} ({More natural seems:} 14... Qf7 {When White keeps slight pressure
with the help of:} 15. Ng3 Bxf3 16. Qxf3) 15. Ng3 ({One interesting way to
benefit from the slightly awkward position of the black queen was:} 15. a4 $5 {
Since the queen needs to guard g7 White has the time to open the queenside.
After:} Qf7 16. b5 axb5 17. axb5 O-O 18. bxc6 bxc6 {White at least weakens
the opponent's pawn chain.}) 15... Bf7 {Carlsen hopes to use the knights as
tempo-gainers when advancing his kingside passer. However, So is the one to
open the game after:} 16. Qd2 g6 17. Nh2 h5 18. f4 exf4 ({Or else White will
seize the f-file:} 18... O-O-O 19. fxe5 fxe5 20. Rf2) 19. Qxf4 O-O-O {It does
not seem particularly scary for Black. After all, he castled, his king is safe,
he is ready to start his kingside assault. However:} 20. e5 $1 {[%csl Re4]
[%cal Rg3e4] Throws a spanner in his plans.} f5 {The only move.} ({As:} 20...
Nxe5 $2 {drops material due to:} 21. Qxf6 Qd6 22. Rae1) 21. Nf3 Qe7 22. Rae1
Rde8 ({The computer recommends to seize a bit of space on the kingside first
with:} 22... h4 23. Ng5 Bg8 24. Ne2 Kb8) {As now:} 23. h4 $1 {[%csl Re5,Rg5,
Rh4][%cal Rf3g5] Fixes all the valuable dark squares in White's favour. The
dangerous passer and the superb blockade promise White long-term positional
plus.} ({It is too early for:} 23. e6 Bxe6 24. Ng5 Qf6) 23... Bd5 {Active, but
a vulnerable spot for the bishop.} ({No matter how ugly it was, but:} 23... Bg8 {
should have been preferred with the idea to block the e5 pawn after:} 24. Ng5
Nf8) 24. Ng5 c5 ({The delicate position of the bishop tells in the line:} 24...
Nf8 25. Qe3 {The queen frees the f4 square with a tempo:} Kb8 26. Ne2 $1 Ne6
27. c4 Nxg5 28. Qxg5 Qxg5 29. hxg5 Be6 30. Nf4 {[%csl Re6,Gf4] leads to
complete domination of the knight over the bishop.}) 25. Re3 {A pity!} ({
So far everything was done perfectly well and the energetic:} 25. e6 $1 Nb6 26.
c4 Bc6 27. Qe3 {would have fixed White's edge.} ({Also good would be:} 27. Ne2)
) 25... b5 {Carlsen seizes his chance and gets some air on the queenside.} 26.
Ne2 Bb7 27. Nc3 {Missing one more chance to achieve a completely dominant
position.} ({Which would be the case after:} 27. bxc5 $1 Qxc5 28. d4 Qc6 29.
Qf2 Nb6 30. Rc3 Qd7 31. Nf4 {Just in time.} Nd5 32. Rc5 {[%csl Gc5,Gf4,Gg5]
White's superb pieces will quickly organize the advance of the central passers.
}) 27... cxb4 28. axb4 Nf6 $1 {The world champion spots an even better route
for his knight.} 29. Rfe1 Ng4 30. R3e2 c5 {Obvious, but Black there is a small
detail...} ({Strong was to centralize his pieces with:} 30... Rd8 $1 {Then:}
31. e6 {can be met with:} Rhe8 {Intending to surround the pawn. What's more
important is that the active try:} 32. Nf7 {Backfires due to:} Qxh4 $1 33. Nxd8
Rxd8 34. e7 Re8 {followed by Kc8-b8 (out of the checks) and g6-g5!}) 31. e6
cxb4 {And with very little time on the clock So demonstrates how brilliant he
is with:} 32. Nf7 $3 Qc7 $1 {The only defense.} ({The main idea behind the
sacrifice is revealed in the line:} 32... bxc3 33. Nd6+ Kd8 34. Nxe8 Rxe8 35.
Qb8+ Bc8 {The attack seems over, but:} 36. Re5 $1 {Transfers fresh troops and
forces Black to part with his queen:} Nxe5 37. Rxe5 Qxe6 38. Rxe6 Rxe6 39. Kf2
{Next White brings his king all the way to f7 and wins ;)}) 33. Qxc7+ Kxc7 34.
Nxh8 Rxh8 35. Nd1 {So won the exchange but nothing is determined yet as the
black bishop is too strong and the queenside passers might become rogue.} Re8
36. e7 Bd5 37. Ne3 {One little inaccuracy and all the advantage is thrown away.
} ({The other route for the knight would have won So a couple of tempos, and
most likely the game:} 37. Nf2 $1 Nxf2 ({If:} 37... a5 {The knight changes his
mind:} 38. Nh3 a4 39. Nf4 Bf7 40. Ne6+ {And manages to swap off the more
dangerous black minor piece.} Bxe6 41. Rxe6 {Thus stopping the black passers
and winning.}) 38. Kxf2 a5 39. Kg3 {In comparison to the game the white king
is two moves ahead and has a clear path towards the kingside and the e-passer.}
) 37... Nxe3 38. Rxe3 a5 39. Kf2 a4 {With second on the clock one pushes the
pawns without any fear.} 40. Kg3 ({The counter-intuitive:} 40. Rb1 $1 {would
have slowed the passers down, say:} b3 ({Or:} 40... a3 41. Rxb4 a2 42. Re1) 41.
cxb3 Bxb3 42. Re5) 40... a3 41. Kf4 b3 {Carlsen is safe, he can no longer lose.
Or so it seems...} 42. cxb3 b4 43. d4 Kd6 44. Re5 a2 {Remember, passers move
on their own in time-trouble.} ({The clear-cut draw would have been achieved
with the help of:} 44... Bxb3 45. Rb5 a2 46. Rxb4 Rxe7 47. Ra1 Re4+ 48. Kg5
Rg4+ 49. Kf6 Bd5) 45. Ra1 ({Alas, White did not have enough time to find the
Votava-like:} 45. R5e3 $3 Be4 46. R3e2 $3 {Then:} Bb1 {Seems to even win for
Black but So has a wonderful way to co-ordinate his rook:} 47. Re6+ Kd5 48. Ra6
Kxd4 49. Rc1 $3 {The king is in a mating net. Now best is:} Kd5 ({A curious
mate is:} 49... Rxe7 50. Rd6#) ({Whereas:} 49... Kd3 50. Rd6+ Ke2 51. Rcd1 $1 {
is also unstoppable mate.}) {But after:} 50. Rc7 $1 {Black is in zugzwang and
has to self-destruct.}) 45... Bxb3 46. Rb5 Rxe7 47. Rxb4 Re4+ 48. Kg5 Rg4+ {
Now once more Black is safe but both players keep on playing for the win.} 49.
Kf6 Rg3 ({To the above-mentioned draw would have led:} 49... Bd5) 50. Rb5 Bc4
51. Rc5 Bd5 52. Ra5 Bb3 (52... Rxg2 {was possible at once.}) 53. Rc1 Rxg2 54.
Rcc5 Rg1 55. Ra6+ Kd7 56. Ra7+ Kd6 57. Ra6+ Kd7 58. Rca5 ({In the heat of the
battle So rejects the perpetual check.} 58. Ra7+) 58... Bc4 59. Ra7+ Kd6 60.
Ra8 f4 61. Rd8+ {And then there was no more perpetual.} ({So should have taken
the draw at last:} 61. Rc5 $1 Kd7 ({But not:} 61... f3 $4 62. Rd8#) 62. Ra7+)
61... Kc7 62. Rda8 f3 63. Rxa2 Bxa2 64. Rxa2 Kd6 {The white king is left out
of the game, Carlsen wins this epic game.} 0-1

