{[%evp 0,40,29,25,28,19,21,8,25,4,8,12,16,-1,-1,0,16,-24,-8,-6,-5,2,16,-7,31,
-51,-44,-44,-37,-76,-77,-99,-101,-89,-78,-74,-72,-57,-25,-19,-55,-92,-81]} 1.
e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O
9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. dxe5 ({Another way to reach the Rauzer
system is:} 12. Nbd2 Nc6 13. dxc5 ({After:} 13. a3 $6 cxd4 14. cxd4 exd4 15.
Nb3 Nd7 16. Nbxd4 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Bf6 {the activity of the black pieces
outweighs the weakness of the d6 pawn.}) 13... dxc5 14. Nf1 Be6 15. Ne3 Rad8
16. Qe2 c4 17. Nf5 ({Black is not worried about:} 17. Ng5 h6 $1 18. Nxe6 fxe6
19. b3 Bc5 20. bxc4 b4 $1 $15 {a blockading idea suggested by Kholmov (see
next clip.)}) 17... Rfe8 {A solid move.} ({Although Black did excellent as
well after:} 17... Bxf5 18. exf5 Rfe8 19. Ng5 Nb8 20. Ne4 $5 Nbd7 21. Be3 Nxe4
22. Bxe4 Nc5 23. Qf3 Nxe4 24. Qxe4 Bc5 25. Bxc5 Qxc5 26. Rad1 {in Stein,
L-Smyslov,V Mar del Plata 1966}) 18. Nxe7+ ({More fighting is:} 18. Bg5 {
Although there Black should be OK after both:} Nh5 $5 ({Or} 18... Nd7 {[%cal
Gd7c5,Gc5d3]})) 18... Nxe7 19. Ng5 $2 {Now Black can save his bishop.} Bc8 20.
a4 h6 21. Nf3 Ng6 22. axb5 axb5 23. Nh2 {Then a typical manoeuvre follows:} Nd7
$1 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gd7c5,Gc5d3] Once that the black knight occupies the d3
square it is only him who can be better. The white light-squared bishop is
locked for good, the attack is non-existent and sooner or later White will
need to swap off the annoying knight.} 24. g3 Nc5 25. Qh5 Nd3 $1 $17 {[%csl
Gd3]} 26. Re2 Qc6 27. Nf1 Rd6 {It is Black who prepares the kingside assault
now!} 28. Bxd3 {However Black now gets a defended passer on the top of his
other advantages.} cxd3 29. Re3 Nf4 $1 {With crushing attack.} 30. gxf4 exf4
31. Re1 Rg6+ 32. Ng3 Rxe4 33. Bxf4 Bb7 34. Rxe4 Qxe4 35. Kf1 Qg2+ 36. Ke1 Re6+
37. Kd2 Qxf2+ 38. Kxd3 Qxf4 39. Qg4 Re3+ 40. Kc2 Qxg3 {0-1 (40) Vasiukov,
E-Kholmov,R USSR 1969}) 12... dxe5 13. Nbd2 Be6 14. Nh2 c4 $1 {Fixing the d3
square.} 15. Qf3 Nb7 $1 {[%cal Gb7c5,Gc5d3] This knight looks even better on
d3.} 16. Ndf1 Nc5 17. Bg5 Rad8 18. Rad1 h6 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Ng4 Bg5 {It makes
sense to preserve the bishop pair as the game will be opened sooner or later.}
21. g3 Nd3 22. Bxd3 cxd3 23. Rxd3 Rxd3 24. Qxd3 Bxa2 {With pleasant advantage
for Black thanks to the bishop pair.} 25. h4 Be7 26. Nfe3 h5 27. Nh2 Bc5 28.
Qe2 g6 29. b4 Bxe3 30. Qxe3 Rc8 31. Ra1 Be6 32. Ra3 Qd6 33. Nf3 Rd8 34. Kg2 Qd1
35. Nxe5 Rd2 36. Qf3 Qe1 37. Nd3 Qb1 38. Ne5 Rd6 39. c4 bxc4 40. Rc3 Qxb4 41.
Rc1 Rd2 42. Qf4 Qd6 43. Nxc4 Qxf4 44. gxf4 Rd4 45. Ne3 Rxe4 46. Ra1 Bc8 47. Kg3
Rb4 48. f5 gxf5 49. Nd5 Rg4+ 50. Kh3 Kg7 51. Ne7 Bd7 52. Rxa6 f4 53. Rd6 Be6
54. Nc6 f3 55. Kh2 Rg2+ 56. Kh1 Rxf2 57. Ne5 Rf1+ 58. Kh2 f2 0-1

