{[%evp 0,92,24,24,2,18,17,16,18,-2,7,0,15,-1,-6,3,6,-28,-31,-15,-2,-8,5,2,27,
17,45,-28,-39,-22,-22,-18,1,6,14,22,30,40,39,-102,-106,-97,-117,-122,-124,-117,
-111,-103,-97,-119,-73,-116,-98,-91,-107,-115,-115,-115,-115,-107,-102,-123,
-145,-129,-123,-106,-109,-85,-75,-115,-75,-75,-129,-107,-106,-117,-124,-148,
-166,-166,-164,-204,-166,-292,-305,-324,-340,-348,-260,-373,-243,-353,-565,
-646,-557]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7.
Bb3 O-O 8. c3 d6 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. Nbd2 Nc6 13. dxc5 dxc5 14.
Nf1 Be6 ({The knight has been sacrificed prior to this game too. Smyslov used
the idea to solve all his problems in the following game:} 14... Rd8 15. Qe2
Rb8 16. Ne3 g6 17. a4 Bf8 18. axb5 axb5 19. Nh2 Be6 $11 20. Qf3 Bg7 21. Nhg4
Nxg4 22. hxg4 Nd4 $1 {[%csl Rd4]} 23. cxd4 cxd4 24. Bb1 dxe3 25. Bxe3 b4 $11 {
Gipslis,A-Smyslov,V Tbilisi 1967}) 15. Ne3 Rad8 16. Qe2 c4 {[%csl Rd3][%cal
Gf6d7,Gd7c5] A familiar plan. The knight is heading to the d3 square.} 17. Ng5
h6 $5 ({Not the immediate:} 17... Nd4 $2 18. cxd4 exd4 19. e5 $1 d3 (19... Qxe5
20. Nf5 $18 {[%csl Re5,Re6,Re7][%cal Re1e7]}) 20. Nxe6 $1 ({Or even better:} 
20. exf6 dxe2 21. Bxh7+ Kh8 22. Nxe6 fxe6 23. fxe7 Qxe7 24. Bc2 $16 {[%csl Gc1,
Gc2,Ge3,Re7] when White should be winning.}) 20... fxe6 21. exf6 dxe2 (21...
Bxf6 22. Qd1) 22. fxe7 Qxe7 23. Rxe2 {[%csl Gc1,Gc2,Ge3,Re7] Matulovic,
M-Mecking,H Sousse (izt) 1967}) ({Notice that the timid:} 17... Bc8 $2 {
would lead to trouble for Black after:} 18. Nd5 $1 Nxd5 19. exd5 Bxg5 20. Bxg5
Rxd5 21. Qe4 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Re4d5,Re4h7]}) 18. Nxe6 fxe6 {[%csl Rd4,Re5,Re6]
[%cal Re6d5,Re6f5,Re5f4,Re5d4] The central pawns are controlling the important
squares. But they are also ready to start rolling if a chance occurs.} 19. b4 {
A blunder.} (19. a4) (19. b3 Bc5 $5 20. bxc4 b4 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Rc6d4,
Rc5d4]}) 19... Nd4 $3 {A stunning sacrifice which discovers the fundament
behind Black's posiiton. Kholmov's pawns start rolling and he quickly achieves
large advantage.} 20. cxd4 exd4 21. a3 ({Here:} 21. e5 {does not work due to:}
d3 $1 (21... Qxe5 22. Nf5 $1) 22. exf6 Bxf6 23. Qg4 Bxa1 24. Qxe6+ Qf7 25.
Qxf7+ Kxf7 $1 26. Bd1 d2 27. Bxd2 Rxd2 28. Bh5+ g6 29. Rxa1 gxh5 {Black wins-
this is how far Kholmov calculated before sacrificing the knight!}) 21... d3
22. Bxd3 Rxd3 $1 ({Avoiding the possible activity of the white pieces after:} 
22... cxd3 23. Qa2 $1 {[%csl Re6]}) 23. Ng4 Kh7 24. e5 Nxg4 25. Qe4+ g6 26.
Qxg4 Rf5 27. Qe4 Qd7 {[%csl Gc4,Gd3,Gd7,Gf5][%cal Gf5f1,Gd3d1]} 28. Be3 Qd5 29.
Qxd5 Rxd5 $1 {The control over the vital open files coupled with the strong
protected passer and the better bishop promises Black decisive advantage.} ({
Another hurdle has been avoided:} 29... exd5 30. Bc5 $1 {[%cal Re5e6,Re6e7,
Re7e8]}) 30. f4 g5 31. g3 gxf4 32. gxf4 Rf8 33. Kg2 Kg6 34. Rg1 Rd3 35. Kf3+
Kf5 $1 {[%csl Gf5]} 36. Rg7 Bd8 37. Rb7 Rg8 38. Rb8 Rg7 39. a4 h5 40. axb5 axb5
41. Rxb5 Bh4 42. Ke2 Rg2+ 43. Kf1 Rh2 44. Kg1 Re2 45. Bb6 c3 46. Kf1 Rh2 0-1

