{[%evp 0,76,29,36,24,28,26,-1,15,-17,-7,-13,-1,-12,7,-2,11,-29,-24,-8,0,-2,2,
-7,28,19,27,33,32,40,41,25,38,1,-13,-12,5,-3,-3,4,-16,-28,-20,-10,-19,-31,10,5,
-14,-14,-8,3,3,3,3,-42,-7,-51,-70,-58,-20,-22,-25,-12,-24,-90,-90,-81,-86,-83,
-109,-140,-169,-255,-266,-297,-311,-311,-316]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4.
Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. c3 d6 9. h3 h6 (9... Na5 10. Bc2 c5
11. d4 Qc7 12. Nbd2 Re8 13. Nf1 g6 {[%csl Rf1,Rf5,Rh5][%cal Ge7f8,Gf8g7,Rg6f5,
Rg6h5,Rf1g3,Rg3f5,Rg3h5] A favourite manoeuvre by Smyslov who often fianchettoed
his bishop. There are many advantages behind this idea: 1) The bishop has
a strong influence on the White's centre. 2) Black's pieces are not obstructing
each other (the rook is opened). 3) The pawn on g6 strands the white Spanish
knight.} 14. Bh6 Nc4 15. Qc1 exd4 16. cxd4 cxd4 17. b3 Ne5 18. Nxd4 Bb7 19. Qb2
Rac8 {[%cal Gc8c1,Ge8e1] The static weakness of the d6 isolani is compensated
with interest by the active black pieces. Both -c and -e files are wonderful
for the rooks, the bishops are also optimal on the long diagonals.} 20. Rad1 {
Overambitious.} ({Perhaps Keres should have switched back to the defence with:
} 20. Rac1 Qc3 21. Qxc3 Rxc3 22. Bb1 $11) 20... d5 $1 {[%csl Rc2] The d5 break
not only clears Black's only weakness but it also opens the road to his more
active pieces to enter the battle.} 21. exd5 (21. f4 Nc6 {[%csl Rc2]}) 21...
Nxd5 22. Bb1 (22. f4 Bb4 (22... Nd7 $5 {[%csl Rc2,Rd4,Rf6,Rg1][%cal Re7f6,
Rf6b2,Re7c5] might be even simpler when White can hardly defend.}) 23. Rxe5
Rxe5 24. fxe5 Bc3 25. Qc1 Qb6 26. Be3 Nxe3 27. Qxe3 Bxd4 28. Rxd4 Rxc2 29. Nd2
Rxa2 30. Kh2 $17) 22... Bb4 23. Bd2 Bc3 24. Bxc3 Nxc3 25. Rc1 Qc5 $1 $19 {
[%csl Rd4] All the black pieces are on commanding squares. No wonder he
quickly finds winning tactics.} 26. Ne2 (26. Qd2 Red8) 26... Nf3+ $1 {[%csl
Rc1,Re2,Rg1]} 27. gxf3 Rxe2 28. Rxe2 Nxe2+ 29. Qxe2 Qg5+ 30. Kh2 Rxc1 31. Be4
Bc8 32. Bd3 Qh5 33. Qe3 Rc3 34. Qd4 Qxf3 35. Be4 Qf4+ 36. Ng3 b4 37. Kg2 Be6
38. Qxb4 Rc8 39. Qe7 Qe5 40. Qb7 a5 41. h4 {0-1 (41) Keres,P-Smyslov,V
Petropolis 1973}) 10. d4 Re8 11. Nbd2 Bf8 12. Nf1 Bd7 13. Ng3 Na5 14. Bc2 c5
15. b3 Nc6 16. Be3 ({Another game of Smyslov went:} 16. d5 Ne7 17. Be3 Qc7 18.
b4 cxb4 19. cxb4 Nc8 20. a4 Nb6 $132) 16... cxd4 17. cxd4 exd4 18. Nxd4 (18.
Bc1 Qc7 19. Bb2 d5 $11) 18... d5 $1 {Same central blow equalizes in full.} 19.
exd5 Nb4 20. Nc6 Nxc6 21. dxc6 Bxc6 $11 22. Qd4 Qd5 23. Qxd5 Nxd5 24. Be4 Nb4
25. Bxc6 Nxc6 26. Nf5 $6 {[%csl Ra2,Rb3] White does not sense the danger and
continues playing as if nothing happened.} ({He should have tried to get rid
of the queenside pawns instead with:} 26. a4 $1 {[%csl Ga4,Ga6,Gb3,Gb5][%cal
Ga4b5,Ga6b5]}) 26... Nb4 $1 {[%csl Ra1,Ra2][%cal Ra1a2] Now there are problems
with White's queenside.} 27. Nd4 (27. Rec1 Rac8 28. a4 Nc2 29. Ra2 Nxe3 30.
Rxc8 Rxc8 31. Nxe3 Rc1+ 32. Kh2 Rb1 $17 {[%csl Rb3]}) 27... Bc5 {[%csl Ra1,Rc2,
Rd4,Re1][%cal Rc5d4,Rb4c2]} 28. Red1 (28. Rec1 Bxd4 29. Bxd4 Re2 {[%csl Ra2,
Rc2][%cal Rb4c2,Rb4a2,Re2a2]}) 28... Nd5 29. Rac1 ({Tactics works for Black in
case of:} 29. Rd3 Nxe3 30. fxe3 Rxe3 $1 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Rc5g1]}) 29... Ba3 $1
{Fixes the weaknesses.} 30. Rc6 Nb4 {[%csl Ra2,Ga3,Rb3,Gb4] Black pieces look
strange but in reality their initiative cannot be stopped.} 31. Rc7 Rad8 $1 32.
Rf1 (32. Rd2 Nd5 33. Nc6 Rd6 34. Ra7 Nxe3 35. Rxd6 Bxd6 36. fxe3 Rxe3 {[%csl
Rg1][%cal Rd6g3,Re3e1,Re1g1]} 37. Ra8+ Kh7 38. Kf2 Bc5 39. Kf1 Rc3 40. Rxa6
Rc1+ 41. Ke2 Rc2+ 42. Kf3 f5 $17) 32... Nxa2 33. Nc2 (33. Ra1 Bd6) 33... Bb2 {
[%csl Ra1][%cal Rb2a1]} 34. Rc6 a5 35. Rc5 Rc8 36. Rxc8 Rxc8 37. Nd4 Bxd4 38.
Bxd4 Nc1 0-1

